I began to develop some rash on my lower right leg, but thought it was Poison Ivy at first as that was what it looked like to me (even though it really was too early for it to have begun to sprout at that point as well as having had long pants on when I had been out in the yard). My regular doctor prescribed a 10 day script of Prednisone and it began to get better. A week or so afterward was when I received my 2nd dose of Pfizer (4/9/21) and the rash suddenly got much, MUCH worse - and it was everywhere! Legs, arms, torso. It itched INCREDIBLY badly. I asked my doctor for another script of Prednisone, but evidently they are remiss to give too much of that out for very long. I then went to a dermatologist that prescribed some topical cream (Desoximetasone) that did and continues to help. They also began to give me UV light treatments 2-3 times a week at increasing time amounts. It initially seemed to help but then began to get too painful, especially when the rash was particularly raging, so I stopped doing those and asked for more Prednisone. They eventually wrote me up for another stint of it though it seemed far less effective at this point. I was able to get into a different dermatologist at this point and had them examine me too. They took punch biopsies in both my arm and torso, which showed positive for Chronic Urticara. They started me on a heavy rotation of various antihistamines (at one point I was at 12 doses of 24 hour tablets a day) which never really seemed to do much. Knocked the itchiness down at that point, but the rash was always present and flared on a weekly-ish basis. They then prescribed a multi-week prescription of Cyclosporin which also never seemed to do that much. It has been 9 months now, and it continues to be (on a semi-weekly basis) just as bad as it ever was.
LAB_DATA: Punch biopsy on both right arm and torso. Collected on 9/21/21 Diagnosis of both: Skin; superficial and mid perivascular dermatitis with rare eosinophils. Comment: Similar features are shown on both biopsies. The infiltrate is confined mostly to the superficial and mid dermis with only minimal epidermal changes; therefore, a dermal hypersensitivity reaction such as due to a drug or arthropod bite is favored over aneczematous process.

Patient received vaccine at 10:31 AM. He stated before receiving the shot he was anxious. Within a few minutes of receiving the vaccine and sitting  down in a chair in the vaccination area, the patient suddenly dropped his phone and started sliding down the chair. His friend caught him before he fell out of the chair and was able to safely get him to the ground with no damage. He immediately laid down on the floor and I came over and noticed he was pale, sweating, and his pupils were enlarged. He stated he had been slightly dizzy before he fainted and had not eaten or drank anything today besides a coffee. I had the patient lay down and elevate his legs and we immediately got him water. 911 services were called and patient drank water and started eating some crackers before EMS arrived. EMS did a thorough medical evaluation including blood pressure , pulse, and oxygen which were normal. Patient was not diabetic and has no history of low blood sugars so they didn't test his blood sugar. The patient stayed supine for about 30 minutes while drinking and eating. EMS ensured he was able to sit up before leaving. Patient finished 2 bottles of water and ate crackers during the 1 hour after the adverse event and his color returned to normal as well as pupils. Patient was provided a water bottle before leaving and I ensured he was okay walking and was feeling back to normal before leaving. I provided him information for follow up and patient was going to shop in store for a little longer and knew how to contact me right away. Patient was with family when he left and he was aware of need to continue to hydrate throughout day.
LAB_DATA: EMS took vitals (blood pressure, oxygen saturation, and pulse) which were within normal limits.

Pt stable.Pt states her throat feels dry, tongue swollen Pt taken to the ED ~12:00  In the ED: 45-year-old female with a history of allergic reaction to tree nuts coming in now by ambulance from her vaccination clinic where she had a scheduled appointment for COVID-19 booster shot.  20 minutes after getting the booster shots she developed sensation of tongue swelling and tingling.  However she reports that lips and tongue and mouth did not look swollen.  She was immediately given an epi shot and it quickly resolved all of her symptoms.  The shot was given at 11:30 AM by her doctor.  No other medications were given.  She has no symptoms at all at this time.  Symptoms were mild nonradiating described as possible anxiety or allergic reaction.  She denies any ingestion of substances with tree nuts.  Did not have any reaction to any Covid 19 vaccinations in the past. No worsening factors were reported.  Symptoms were not associate with any rash, trouble breathing or swallowing or speaking or drooling shortness of breath or cough or wheezing abdominal pain passing out syncope lightheadedness or other complaints at all. 13 hours after injection, symptoms began. First, sudden onset of intense fever, followed by chills. Body temperature remained volatile for about 2-3 hours, switching between extreme hot and cold in intervals of 15 minutes or so. In addition, within the first 30 minutes of the initial fever, high levels of pain occurred from base of the skull down through neck, shoulders, upper back, and upper left arm (side that received injection). This pain was similar to muscular body aches you would have with a flu infection, but much more intense. Any attempt at movement was excruciating - I could not even move my arm or adjust positions without crying outloud or whimpering. Around 14 hours post-injection, a different kind of pain appeared: this seemed like a nerve problem of sorts. There was a sensation of pins and needles throughout my entire body, not just concentrated near the injection site. It was somewhat like the sensation we have when a limb "falls asleep" and produces tingling pain, but again, the intensity of the sensation was notable. The pins-and-needles, full-body nerve pain lasted for about 2 or 3 hours. The muscular pain that was concentrated around my neck, shoulders, and injection site lasted for about 5 hours, after which the arm that had received the injection was still very stiff and sore for the next day. However, the soreness in neck, shoulders, and upper back subsided after about 5 hours. The fever and chill cycles began to slow down after about 3 hours and stabilized within about 6 hours. I didn't attempt to treat any of the side effects, partly because I was immoblized by pain and fatigue, and partly because I wasn't sure if there were more effects to follow. The reaction began about 13 hours after receiving the vaccine, and with the exception of soreness at injection site, the symptoms resolved by about 18 hours post-injection.

Symptoms began 10 hours after injection.  At 4:30am, I awoke suddenly, and almost immediately noticed a high fever coming on. (My body temperature is regularly 96.7 F, but registered up to 99.8 F at the highest point I measured). Within 30 minutes of the fever, I began experiencing rapid cycling between fever and chills. The chills were so strong that my whole body was shivering uncontrollably and the surface of my skin was painful. Within the first hour after onset of the fever, I began experiencing muscular aches from my neck down into the injection site, making it difficult to move. Around the same time,  I began to experience what I would describe as nerve pain - a "pins and needles" tingling sensation that I felt throughout my entire body. The surface of my skin was especially noticeably painful (the fever and chill cycles continued during the muscular and nerve pain). The rapid changes in body temperature began to slow and reduce in intensity after about 5 hours. The nerve pain lasted for about 3 hours, during which I was unable to rest, unable to move effectively, but also unable to stay completely still because of the sharpness of the tingling nerve pains. The muscular soreness around my neck, shoulders, and injection site lessened throughout the day and seemed mostly resolved by approx 10 hours after onset (about 20 hours post-injection). However, full-body muscular soreness set in around 22 hours post-injection - I suspect this might have been due to my muscles tensing up so much and so frequently during the chill cycles. Whole body felt sore until about 30 hours post-injection. I DID experience bad side effects from my second dose of the Moderna vaccine and the side effects from the booster are very similar in nature. The differences are: with dose #2, side effects began 13 hrs post-injection, were very severe for about 6 hours, and almost completely subsided by 24hrs post-injection; by contrast, side effects from the Moderna booster began earlier (10 hours post-injection) and lasted much longer (still experiencing pain 30+ hours after injection), but the effects did not seem as intense with the booster vs the 2nd full dose (2nd dose pain was too strong to move at all, booster di. One exception: the chills that came from the booster were very extreme and caused significant pain and discomfort around the surface of my skin, I did not treat the side effects with any medication or other techniques.
PRIOR_VAX: Fever, chills, muscle aches, nerve pain, stiffness/immobilization resulting from Moderna COVID vaccine dose #2 on 4/29/2021, pat

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have been a regular exercise and heart healthy man for several years. My cholesterol levels were not dangerously high and a recent LDL lab was 128. The symptom started to show up during normal walk in next days and even got worse at showers as well. I went to a local health care facility and ended up with a stent in my right coronary artery. Otherwise I was a roll model to our community youngsters for daily activities of workouts, playing soccer or basketball at least 3 to 4 days a week. I want CDC to do more studies even in the minority population who complains about complications of covid vaccinations.  I will available on my phone (NUMBER) if anybody from CDC wants to talk with me regarding my case.

On Friday, December 17, 2021 client received her Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine booster (LOT #: FF8841) at 12:45 PM in her left deltoid. Client also received a Fluarix Quadravalent (LOT #: 7557A) vaccine in her right deltoid. During assessment questions, client stated she has a medical history of high blood pressure and diabetes type 2 and takes Lantus and Metformin. Client states she is also allergic to nuts and cigarette smoking. Client also mentioned after her first and second Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine, she experienced slight tingling on her tongue. She stated she went home and took Benadryl and the tingling sensation subsided. Client to be observed for 30 minutes after vaccination. At approximately 12:52 PM, while in Observation Area, client stated to EMT and PHN felt "7 out of 10" throat constriction, facial flushing and lips tingling. Client was brought to anti-gravity chair and vitals started. At 12:53 PM: BP: 162/80, HR 94, O2: 97%, RR: 16. At 12:57 PM, RN administered 50 mg/ml of Diphenhydramine in client's right arm and explained the fast-acting nature and drowsiness effect. At 12:59 PM, BP: 162/80, RR: 16. client stated constriction still a "7 out of 10" but is calm and speaking full and complete sentences. At 1:09 PM, BP: 164/100, HR: 95, O2 sat: 98% client stated she felt "5 out of 10" throat constriction, lips "slightly" tingly still. Client stated she spoke to her PCP about previous reactions to Covid-19 vaccine and stated her PCP still recommended to receive her booster dose and take Benadryl or Ibuprofen as needed. Client reported similar history and baseline of tingly lips for a "few hours" after vaccination. At 1:14 PM, BP: 166/98, HR: 98, O2 sat: 98%, RR: 16. Client feels "5 out of 10" throat constriction. At 1:22 PM BP: 164/102, HR:91, O2 sat: 98%, RR: 16. At 1:25 PM, client stated she still felt "5 out of 10" throat constriction but felt stable to leave. No further interventions needed. PHN educated patient on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client left vaccination site with a steady gait at approximately 1:30 PM.
PRIOR_VAX: anaphaxlysis

I began developing hives all over my body and swelling on my lips and eyes. When it was especially bad I would feel it internally in my chest, like I had swallowed a pill that got stuck at the base of my throat. The hives and swelling were always worst in the morning and would migrate by the next day. It got worse when I did not sleep enough or drank alcohol, but still occurred even without these triggers. My reactions peaked May into June where my hives got so bad at points that I couldn't move my hands - as if my hands were just two giant hives. When I had bloodwork done my inflammation numbers were off the charts, but nothing else was abnormal. I began on a regimen of steroids (only 4 days) and antihistamines (consistently) that moderated but did not stop my reactions. By late July it was mostly under control, with hives showing up roughly once every 1-2 weeks. Since then the longest period I've gone without a flare up is 1 month. It seems to get worse around my menstrual cycle. I am now only taking the antihistamines as needed when I wake up with hives or swelling.
LAB_DATA: All bloodwork done by my General Practitioner came back normal, except for my inflammation numbers. She did bloodwork twice in May, 2021. I visited an ENT/allergist who did an allergy test in September - I was not allergic to anything. She performed more extensive bloodwork in October and everything came back normal. In November I visited a Rheumatologist who tested me for all autoimmune disorders, all of which I was negative for. She also tested my inflammation numbers which as of last month were back in normal range. I've been told to consult an immunologist and a naturopath.
ALLERGIES: None, tested prior to vaccination and retested since - No allergies to anything other than slight seasonal.

69 M with PMH sig for DM, Type II, aortic stenosis s/p bioprosthetic valve, COVID on 2/8/21 had COVID vaccination with sudden onset loss of appetite, nausea, diarrhea, loss of sense of taste, chills persisting for 1-2 weeks prior to evaluation.   Initial evaluation with elevated procalcitonin (9.904), CRP (9.1), ESR (77), ALT (45), Bili (1.3), WBC (12.8>11.5) neutrophil predominant (10.0).   CT chest/abdomen to r/o occult infection largely unremarkable.    Patient received medrol dose pack with worsening fever/chills/confusion after completion of steroid course.  Blood Culture positive for streptococcus gallolyticus bacteremia.  Patient was admitted to ICU,  received IV ABX then ceftriaxone for 14 days post discharge.   TTE/TEE negative for infective endocarditis.   Patient recovered with residual fatigue at last evaluation.    *17. Streptococcus gallolyticus subsp. gallolyticus Sgg (formerly known as S. bovis type I) is the main causative agent of septicemia and infective endocarditis (IE) in elderly and immunocompromised persons. It belongs to the few opportunistic bacteria, which have been strongly associated to colorectal cancer (CRC). A literature survey covering a period of 40 years (1970?2010) revealed that 65% of patients diagnosed with an invasive Sgg infection had a concomitant colorectal neoplasia. Sgg is associated mainly with early adenomas and may thus constitute an early marker for CRC screening.  Fecal occult blood positive 10/04/2019.  Recommend colonoscopy.
HISTORY: DM, aortic stenosis s/p bioprosthetic valve

Patient received x2 Pfizer Covid vaccines on 4/7/21 and 4/29/21 with out any adverse events.  She then received her 3rd shot (booster) on 12/10/21.  On 12/11/21, she developed a headache.  Over the course of the next several days, she started having intermittent numbness on the right side of her body on 12/15.  She presented to emergency department on 12/15 PM where she then had a seizure.  MR, MRA, MRV showed extensive thrombus of saggital sinus.  She was started on Keppra and heparin drip and was admitted to the ICU.  Lab testing was unremarkable, including platelets which were normal.  The patient also has a family history of VTE and was on birth control pills.  On 12/16, she had LUE and BLE weakness. Repeat MRI on 12/16 showed increased volume of cortical acute infarction so patient was taken to interventional radiology for superior sagittal sinus thrombectomy with resultant good flow through SSS. .  On 12/17, the patient reports headache is improved. BLE and LUE weakness improved after procedure.  Hypercoag labs sent.  Plan is to stop oral contraceptives permanently and patient is to be worked up for hypercoagulable state (some workup will need to be completed outpatient).  No evidence of ongoin seizures.  The patient will be treated with heparin drip and ultimately will be converted to warfarin for anticoagulation.  On day of this report (12/17/21), the patient remains hospitalized and is transferring from ICU to general medicine floor.
LAB_DATA: See summary of event. 12/15 platelets 366, 12/17 platelets 270.

I was given IV benadryl and steroids, then released with a course of prednisone. As with the first dose I had serious fatigue and flu-like symptoms that lasted weeks. My rash resolved in about 2 weeks.   I also got 2 cold sores on my upper lip. I got a cold sore after the first dose, too. I don't get them often so this was concerning to have 2 in such a short time span.   Fatigue and brain fog continued to be a serious problem.   In May, I had a regularly scheduled appointment with my endocrinologist. My hypothyroidism, which is controlled with medication, was found to have suddenly gotten worse. My TSH which was 1.0 the last time it was checked (in 2020) had jumped to over 10. The only thing that I had done differently was get vaccinated. My dose of synthroid was increased to 200mcg. I had another appointment a month later and my tsh was back to normal but the brain fog and fatigue had continued. My doctor thought the sudden jump in tsh might be related to the vaccine since my thyroid condition is autoimmune.
CUR_ILL: Large rash at injection site and extended fatigue and flu-like symptoms after Moderna COVID-19 vaccine dose 1.

My primary care physician added Losartan to meds (early July 2021), resulting in almost immediate BP  bottom readings in high 50s-low 60s. Physician changed to lower dose of Losartan after only 3 days on higher dose.  Between April 2021-July 2021, I was miserable with chest pain so I took Benadryl, 2-325 mg doses of aspirin, + 1 Aleve which helped with inflammation, even though it took several months to get any relief. Since early July 2021, I am still experiencing  intermittent chest pains. I go back on Aleve & aspirin which seems to help. I firmly believe vaccine damaged what was a perfectly healthy heart. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Got the vaccine on 11/04 and chose Pfizer because I had such a bad reaction to Moderna dose 1 and 2. After my booster, I had serious fatigue and a small rash at the injection site. I had nightly fevers for 3 nights. On 11/27 I woke up with a cold sore forming on the tip of my nose. I had a telehealth appointment and the doctor informed me this was a sign of shingles (Hutchinson sign). I went immediately to urgent care. They did a corneal dye exam and found no lesions on my cornea. The physician prescribed a 7 day prescription of valacyclovir 1g tablets x3/day. I had flu like symptoms and fatigue but did not develop a cold sore on my nose, or any rash at all. I had chicken pox as a child (about 5yrs) and am unvaccinated against chicken pox as well as shingles. I have never had shingles before.   Tuesday 12/14 I woke up feeling ill and had pain behind my left ear.  Wednesday 12/15 I noticed little blisters behind my ear. I went to urgent care and they diagnosed me with a recurrence of shingles, but said my ear drum was clear. Physician prescribed me another round of valacyclovir 1gm 3/day. It is now day 4 and my entire left side of my face is hugely swollen, including my outer ear. I have itching and the skin is hot red and raised but hasn't yet developed blisters. It's an 8/10 on the pain scale. I have had several serious stressors in the time leading up to this, including travel and loss of a close friend, so my immune system is probably down. I also haven't been eating or sleeping well and I didn't give myself a chance to recover after the booster.
PRIOR_VAX: Moderna Covid-19 vaccine dose 1 and 2.

No medications were administered at this time. Patient had called her father to come pick her up so she wouldn't have to drive home on her own. Another set of vital signs at 11:15 am: blood pressure 140/96, heart rate 127, respirations 18, SPO2 100%. Patient did not report any past medical history and stated she does not currently have primary care physician. She did report some nausea, confusion and disorientation, fainting with the first Moderna shot, but no side effects with the second Moderna vaccination. Patient's car was parked in a safe location, she was walked to her father's car. Per Safety Officer and Paramedic, patient was told she needs to get checked out by a doctor to follow up on symptoms as soon as possible. admitted through the emergency room for progressive radiographic  infiltrates, hypoxemic respiratory failure and what appears to be  superimposed COVID pneumonia.  Her history dates back about 2 weeks ago.   There was apparently an outbreak of COVID at the Center and  they have been screening their residents regularly.  She was screened on  Tuesday the 23rd, although at that time she was having absolutely no  cardiovascular or chest complaints.  She went and enjoyed  Thanksgiving with  her family on Thursday and was reported later that day that she was COVID  positive.  She went back to her apartment and has been  sequestered there since that time.  She did well until several days after  Thanksgiving when she started to develop exertional dyspnea and increasing  nonproductive cough.  No fever, no chills, no hemoptysis.  No chest discomfort  of any sort.  Denies palpitations.  She was checking her saturations and they  were dropping into the mid 80s at times and this prompted an ER visit on the  30th.  She wanted to return home after her visit there.  She was saturating  well around 90% prior to discharge.  ABGs at that time revealed a pO2 of 58.5,  pCO2 of 28.  She was given a dose of bamlanivimab and etesevimab (700  mg/1,400 mg) x1 and was discharged back to her apartment.  At rest, she did  pretty well with her O2 sats remaining in the 90+ percent range while, but any activity caused desaturations in the mid 80% range.  I talked  with her son the day before this admission and suggested she go to the  emergency room, but she refused.  On the day of admission, she was still  coughing and short of breath maybe a little worse and she finally agreed to  come in for further evaluation.  She was seen in the ER on the day of  admission and CTA was obtained.  This revealed bilateral interstitial  infiltrates consistent with COVID pneumonia superimposed on her interstitial  changes.  She was given IV azithromycin and Rocephin and I was contacted.  She  was placed on IV heparin and is admitted at this time for further inpatient  treatment.  Her procalcitonin was mildly elevated at 0.12.  CRP was 113.   White count was 7.45 with no shift.  Chemistries looked good.  Renal function  was stable and her troponin was mildly elevated at 0.108.  BNP was normal at  85.  She was admitted with a provisional diagnosis of hypoxemic respiratory  failure secondary to COVID pneumonia with superimposed underlying interstitial  lung disease. She was felt to be sick enough to be in the hospital as we noted.  She was  saturating well on 3 L nasal cannula.  She was begun on Decadron 6 mg daily,  begun empirically on IV antibiotic coverage in light of her elevated sed  inflammatory markers, which may all be secondary to underlying COVID, but we  did cover her with Rocephin and azithromycin.    Her hospital stay was approximately 6 days.  She did get worse for the first  couple of days requiring higher O2 requirements.  She was up to at most 5 L  nasal cannula.  There was never a problem with CO2 retention.  She remained  alert, oriented, and comfortable.  She had a nonproductive cough  intermittently at times and no chest pain or discomfort.  She never had any  febrile course, and all blood cultures remained negative.    We monitored her closely on a daily basis.  She remained on the COVID floor.   She had previously received Regeneron a week before, and the details of this  are outlined in the H and P.    With time, there was slow symptomatic improvement.  She still required oxygen  on the day of discharge, but her O2 requirements were such that we were able  to decrease her rest O2 down to 3 L nasal cannula.  Her pH was 7.44, pCO2 of  31, and pO2 of 62, and she was perfectly comfortable on these settings.  She  will need 4-5 L with activity.    She remained weak and is in need of further home care.  We felt that she may  require skilled care placement, but the family was determined to take her home  with them.  Her daughter took family leave and will be her caretaker, and she  has other children in the area and grandchildren, who can assist in her home  care.  We will arrange for home care as well.  Home O2 was arranged at 3 L at  rest, 4-5 L with exertion as noted.

I started feeling achy joints.  When I first got the booster, I was tired with low energy. In a week to ten days later, there was stiffness in my muscles, that lasted for another week or so. There were no dramatic changes in my diet of exercise. The was a constant pain blocking my concentration. There was an aching and burning in my knees. It was hard to work, I was distracted by the aching burning pain. It was a weird different pain, it continued to escalate. I took Tylenol and Ibuprofen to help with the pain. It did not help for very long. I only took it when it was dramatic and wake me up at night. I realized I didn't know why my knees were hurting, it was making my grouchy and tired. I went to the doctor to see if this was arthritis or something more serious. I called an online nurse in the morning that recommended to go be seen. about my knees. The doctor pressed on my knees and touch around the area. The doctor checked for swelling rash and heat, they were a little swollen but not a lot. My calf and ankles were thick and swollen.  The doctor stated it was not arthritis because there was pain to the touch. She said it seemed to be tendon and muscle.  The doctors stated:  Symptoms are likely musculoskeletal origin; the muscle of concern is the quadriceps. More specifically the vastus medialis, which is one of the four muscles. She recommended daily stretching and strength training and gave me exercises and to follow up in four weeks.

Other foods that are bad, but I can sometimes tolerate are beef, vegetables, milk, cheese, and corn tortillas. When I?m at my worst which lasts 5-10 days and can?t get anything in my system. Pure sugar candy like a Twizzler or Gummy bears can work. The only things I can drink are aloe vera drinks and blue Gatorade.  5. Can?t control emotions ? When I?m at my worst I cry uncontrollably or can?t control my anger to where I stay away from people. I?ve punched through a desk and a wall, flipped furniture over and then end up crying uncontrollably. I wouldn?t do it, but I have suicidal thoughts when I?m like this. When I?m at my best (which still sucks badly) I feel like I?m having a 24/7 panic attack. That feeling is always there and never leaves. 6. Dizziness to where I must hold a wall or sit down. 7. Cold sweats 8. Shaking  9. Get freezing cold in temperatures that shouldn?t bother me. 10. Sometimes the stomach issues hit so hard my entire body tingles like I just grabbed an electric fence.    Timing of symptoms: - Symptoms started late May or early June about a week after my second Pfizer vaccine shot. - Around that time, I also had a very simple hernia surgery.  - Earlier in the spring I had the Inspire System installed for sleep apnea. There is a device installed in my right pectoral muscle that powers the system. It connects to nerves in my neck that control my tongue. It was done by Dr. My operation was difficult because my nerves were a mess, so he had to cut a nerve in my neck that was in the way. I was told that this shouldn?t cause me any issues. I did have to wait 6 weeks before they turned it on to heal because the surgery was so difficult. The Inspire system was turned on fully about a month or so before my symptoms started.  I tried shutting it off for 2 weeks with no luck.  - General timings are completely random. Some days are worse in the morning and some in the evening. I?ve tried to narrow down food, drinks, amount of sleep, weather patterns, stress, and if I?m at my house or my sister?s where we run a company, but I can?t find anything consistent.  Physical activities tend to make symptoms come on faster.  I haven?t been able to exercise since this started.   Attempts to relieve the symptoms. 1.  Sleep ? sometimes helps, sometimes I?m worse when I wake up. 2. Nausea Meds ? I?ve had every over the counter and prescription medication there is. I?ve even had all those medications injected into me at the Emergency Room. None of these helped or even touched the symptoms. 3. Maximum strength prescription antacid. No help whatsoever. 4. Anti-Migraine pills at night. No help 5. Desipramine ? taken at night. No help 6. The only thing that even takes off an edge is cannabis. Before this started, I rarely ever used it.  Now I need it on a daily basis to function as a human.  7. Anti-diarrhea pills. They do nothing to slow it down when I have it, but after a week or 2 when I finally stops, I get constipated.
LAB_DATA: 1.  Colonoscopy:  No problems except hemorrhoids. 2. Upper GI:  Swelling of my stomach and esophagus with no apparent cause. 3. Brain MRI:  normal 4. Pancreas test:  Normal 5. Gastric Emptying test:  Normal 6. Ultrasound:  Normal 7. CT scan:  Normal 8. 2 separate stool samples. ? No parasites or bacteria found. 9. Gall Bladder test - Normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately (within five seconds or less) after intramuscular injection in the left deltoid the patient experienced syncope and then rapidly fell into whole body convulsions. Patient was unresponsive to my voice or touch for about twenty seconds during which I held his wrist to be ready to lower him to the floor gently if necessary as the convulsions slowly subsided.  He was then briefly able to rouse himself to track my face with his eyes, then lapsed back into syncope with lack of muscle tone and a heavy deep breathing. The patient was steady in his chair, though in a slightly awkward position, so I allowed him perhaps thirty seconds or a minute for him to recover. After a time I snapped my fingers at him and he immediately roused enough to sense his situation, but was not fully conscious. He held his finger up indicating that he needed a moment. After another minute or so I addressed him and he was able to open his eyes and reply. He appeared pale, sweaty, and weak but present. I confirmed he did not feel he was in immediate danger and he told me that incidents like this were common for him, and that he would be fine. I found him some orange juice and a bag of frozen peas nearby, and allowed him ten or fifteen minutes alone in the shot room to recover, checking on him every few minutes. After a time he put his sweater back on and seemed steady. He confirmed that he was experiencing no symptoms of hives or swelling in the throat. He remained in the store for five minutes or so then left.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient reported that the reaction was common after prior injections.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I administered the Pfizer 5-11 Covid 19 vaccine (LOT FK5127, EXP 1/31/22) to patient intramuscularly on her left arm on 12/17/21 at 5:26pm. The patient appeared calm and did not show any signs of nervousness while giving the immunization. I gave her a fruit snack as a treat after the immunization. The patient's father, mentioned that they were having a normal conversation together and approximately 5 minutes after the immunization he noticed that she was pale in color and lips were blue. Patient then leaned into her father and fainted into his arms. He mentioned that she did not fall, he laid her on the ground, and called us for help. I immediately left the pharmacy with our immunization cart and supplies to assess the situation and help the patient. The patient appeared to be experiencing syncope. She was pale and mentioned that she was feeling dizziness, nausea, and weakness. While the patient was lying down, I applied cold compresses to her neck, face, and wrist. Patients father, called his wife at 5:38pm and she arrived within 15 minutes. We comforted her and continued to apply cold compresses while she was lying down. Roughly every 15 minutes after lying down, she attempted to sit up but still felt dizziness so she immediately lied back down to feel better. We attempted to get a proper blood pressure reading, but she was unable to sit up. This continued until about 6:45pm. Once patient felt better, Sophie's parents thanked us and dad carried her to the car to go home. I called them at 7:26pm to follow up on patient, they had mentioned that she was feeling a lot better and the color of her skin and lips were back to normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the day of the this 2nd dose, I did feel a slight tingle on the left side of my face. My left arm hurt from the top, all the way through my forearm, and up my middle finger. I went to the the ER the following day and they diagnosed me with  hemiplegic migraines. (I am 32 and have NEVER had migraines) The Friday of that same week I began vomitting, and was still in excruciating pain in my arm and my head.  I went to the ER again and was told it was a migraine.  My right vision has lowered from 20/20, and today is still blurry.  My IPO in my eyes was a 19 on the right side and 18 on the left.  I have treied numerous medicine for the headaches, nausea and vomitting, and arm pain.  I had bowel incontinence 3 times, and was told that my body is now full of inflammation and an autoimmune disorder was triggered.  I have gained 40 lbs since my second vaccine, am swollen, constantly battling headaches, and having multiple doctors appointments to resolve the issues.  I also did not have a period until November 27th,  since my second vaccine.  My life has been completely altered since this second vaccine in a negative way.

varicella-zoster virus (VZV) meningitis; This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article, titled as stated below and refers to a 7-year-old male patient. His past history included febrile seizures at age 13 months.  On an unknown date, at age of 14 months, the patient was vaccinated with his first dose of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX) for prophylaxis (exact dose, route, anatomical location, lot# and expiration date were not reported). On an unknown date at age of 26 months, he experienced febrile seizures. On an unknown date, at age of 49 months, he was vaccinated with measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live (PROQUAD) (exact dose, route, anatomical location, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis.  On an unknown date, he experienced erythematous rash about 4 cm in diameter over the right knee. At a medical clinic, poison ivy was diagnosed and oral prednisolone was prescribed at a daily dosage of 20 mg for 7 days (0.8 mg/kg/day). Cytokine inflammatory profiles in the CSF patient's sample was analyzed. The 10 most elevated cytokines in patient's CSF samples included: interferon gamma (75.76), interleukins: IL-1RA (184.63); IL-6 (90.57), IL-8 (4034.30), IL-10 (75.39), and IL-17F (348.68); chemokines CCL2 (616.79), CXCL9 (81.16), and CXCL10 (1178.58); as well as G-CSF (55.79) (units not provided for all).   On an unknown, 17 days after, he developed a headache, followed a few hours later by low grade fever. Next day, his headaches worsened, and he began to vomit. Vomiting continued over the next 24 h whenever his parents attempted to feed him. When the vomiting persisted into the second day, he was admitted to a local hospital for intravenous (IV) hydration. After spending one night at the local hospital, he was transferred to a medical center. On admission, the child was in obvious pain. His physical examination did not disclose any rashes or abnormalities in major organ systems. Although the neurology examination was difficult to perform, he had mild nuchal rigidity but no focal neurological abnormalities. His non-contrast head computerized tomography (CT) imaging was normal. His initial laboratory testing included the following values: erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR): 14 mm; C-reactive protein (CRP): 0.5 mg/L; white blood cell count = 4000/mm3 with 1790 neutrophils, 1130 lymphocytes, and 380 eosinophils all per mm3. His hemoglobin was 12.2 gm/dL; aspartate aminotransferase /alanine aminotransferase (AST/ALT): 20/30 units/L and his urinalysis was normal. His cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) was hazy with a glucose of 50 mg/dL, total protein of 60 mg/dL, and nucleated cell count of 544 cells/mm3 with mainly lymphocytes. A multiplex meningitis/encephalitis polymerase chain reaction (PCR) was positive for both varicella zoster virus (VZV) and human herpesvirus 6 (HHV6). Because the preliminary diagnosis was VZV meningitis (Herpes zoster meningitis), treatment with acyclovir, intravenous (IV) at 30 mg/kg/day was initiated. His VZV-specific IgM and IgG antibody titers detected by immunofluorescence were positive at titers of 1:4 and 1:64, respectively. Because the Before meningitis panel had a positive HHV6 signal and the metagenomic next-generation sequencing (mNGS) assay detected HHV7 sequences but no HHV6 sequences, testing for both HHV6 and HHV7 antibodies was performed. The patient had detectable IgG antibodies to both HHV6 and HHV7 at a titer of 1:16. The IV acyclovir was stopped after 4 days, when the child was markedly improved and his headaches resolved. He was discharged on a regimen of valacyclovir (500 mg three times daily) for 10 more days. The child was seen several times during the 18 months post discharge. His recovery from meningitis was complete.   The relatedness between the event and suspect vaccines was considered as related as the authors reported that meningitis was caused by the live varicella vaccine virus. The relatedness between the event and prednisolone was considered as related as it was concluded that ingestion of an oral corticosteroid burst 3�4 weeks before onset of vaccine meningitis may be a risk factor and treatment with a prednisolone burst at a relatively high dosage likely allowed latent vaccine virus to reactivate.  Literature report:   A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.  This is one of three cases derived from the same literature article (cross referenced with MARRS# 2112USA005730 and 2007USA012025).; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2112USA005730: US-009507513-2007USA012025:

This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article, titled as stated below and refers to a 12-year-old male patient. No information regarding patient's pertinent medical history, drug reactions, allergies and concomitant medications. On an unknown date, at age of 14 months, the patient was vaccinated with his first dose of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX) for prophylaxis (exact dose, route, anatomical location, lot# and expiration date were not reported). On an unknown date at age of 30 months, he received second dose of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX) (exact dose, route, anatomical location, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the previously healthy patient, presented to the emergency department with a 1-day history of fever, headache, phonophobia and photophobia. Because he had neck stiffness, a lumbar puncture was performed. Laboratory analysis of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) revealed 83 white cells/mm3 (88% lymphocytes). The CSF was tested by the meningitis panel and found to be positive for varicella zoster virus (VZV) and negative for enterovirus, herpes simplex virus, and HHV6, as well as bacteria. The patient was hospitalized, and acyclovir intravenous (IV) (30 mg/kg/day) was initiated. No radiologic studies were ordered. On day 5, he was discharged home; his acyclovir was switched to oral administration for a total treatment course of 14 days. The virus in the CSF was confirmed to be the VZV vaccine strain by Sanger sequencing. Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) analysis for HHV-7 DNA on the CSF was performed; that test was negative. The patient had an extensive immunology evaluation, which showed normal serum immunoglobulin (IG) IgG, IgA, and IgM levels and normal serum levels of vaccine antibodies for all tested antigens (measles, varicella, tetanus, and diphtheria). An extended immunophenotyping showed normal subpopulations of B, T, and NK cells. Finally, genetic analysis was performed by immunology exome sequencing, which included a panel of 356 genes of primary immunodeficiency. However, no errors in innate immune genes or other rare primary immunodeficiencies were discovered; specifically, there were no errors in RNA polymerase III genes. The child had undergone a complete recovery when seen at 1 and 12 months after his hospitalization. A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience. SYMPTOM_TEXT: leaky syringe from needle connection; leaky syringe from needle connection during administration; only a partial dose was received; squirted all over the patient; squirted all over the patient; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of accidental underdose in a 5-year-old female patient who received DTPa-IPV (Kinrix) (batch number H9FM5, expiry date 7th May 2023) for prophylaxis. On 7th December 2021, the patient received Kinrix (intramuscular) and Kinrix Pre-Filled Syringe Device. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pharmaceutical product complaint and syringe connection issue. On an unknown date, the outcome of the accidental underdose, exposure via skin contact, inadvertent exposure to vaccine, pharmaceutical product complaint and syringe connection issue were unknown.     This report is made by GSK without prejudice and does not imply any admission or liability for the incident or its consequences.  Additional details were reported as follows: Registered nurse stated this occurred at the time of administration and only a partial dose was received after the device started leaking, which led to accidental underdose. The patient received a dose of Kinrix, where the vaccine leaked and squirted all over the patient, which led to exposure via skin contact and inadvertent exposure to vaccine. Agent requested return of both the prefilled syringe and needle related to the product complaint and the original packaging without further manipulation/handling. Additionally, patient experienced unexpected non-serious events of Post procedural infection, Post procedural pain. The events Haematospermia occurred on the evening of 22 Oct 2021 after the booster dose of mRNA-1273 vaccine. On 14-Dec-2021, the patient experienced EXPIRED PRODUCT ADMINISTERED (Received expired vaccine administered >12(US)/ hours post puncture). On 14-Dec-2021, EXPIRED PRODUCT ADMINISTERED (Received expired vaccine administered >12(US)/ hours post puncture) had resolved.        For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   No concomitant medication were reported. No treatment information was provided by the reporter.  Patient received expired Moderna COVID-19 vaccine from a vial that was punctured for more than 12 hours (first punctured on 13-DEC-2021 at 2:58PM , and administered on 14-DEC-2021 at 8AM). The vial was initially stored in the refrigerator on  29-Oct-2021.The vial did not undergo any temperature excursions. The vial was stored post puncture in room  temperature. Total amount of time the vial was exposed to room temperature range (8� to 25�C 46� to 77�F) was 17.5 hours.   This case was linked to MOD-2021-414574, MOD-2021-414607, MOD-2021-414618, MOD-2021-141623 (Patient Link).

This spontaneous case reported by a nurse, describes the occurrence of accidental overdose (received 0.5mL Moderna instead of 0.25mL booster dose) and pain in extremity (pain in arm) in a 55-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, batch/lot# 012H21B) for COVID-19  immunization. No medical history reported. On Nov 19, 2021, patient received the third dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 vaccine), intramuscular; 1 dosage form. In November 2021, pain in extremity (pain in arm) resolved. On Nov 19, 2021, accidental overdose (received 0.5mL Moderna instead of 0.25mL booster dose) resolved. The reporter did not provide any causality assessments, concomitant medication or treatment information.

A 34 year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (BNT162B2) 21 days after first dose, administered in deltoid left/ left shoulder (Batch/Lot number: unknown) as dose 2, single for covid-19 immunisation. Relevant medical history included: "augmentation/periareolar mastopexy" (unspecified if ongoing), notes: she underwent augmentation/ peri areolar mastopexy with a sub pectoral 440 cc smooth-walled implant; "gravida 3, para 3" (unspecified if ongoing), notes: healthy gravida 3, para 3 woman. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. Past drug history included: Cefazolin, notes: Preoperative intravenous cefazolin (1 g) was given. The implant pocket was irrigated with triple antibiotic solution (1 g cefazolin, 50,000 U of bacitracin, 80 mg gentamicin); Bacitracin, notes: The implant pocket was irrigated with triple antibiotic solution (1 g cefazolin, 50,000 U of bacitracin, 80 mg gentamicin); Gentamicin, notes: The implant pocket was irrigated with triple antibiotic solution (1 g cefazolin, 50,000 U of bacitracin, 80 mg gentamicin); Povidone-iodine solution. Poly-4-hydroxybutyrate mesh reinforcement was used inside the implant pocket; this product is routinely used by the author for augmentation/mastopexies to support both the parenchyma and the implant position. Tegaderm nipple shields, routinely used by the author for augmentations, were not used in this case due to the need to transpose the nipple-areolar complex. The implant was placed with an insertion funnel through a separate inframammary incision. Postoperatively she did well, and at 6 weeks, postoperative photographs demonstrate good implant position, and at 10 weeks, postop was noted to have good implant position with soft and movable implants (Baker I) bilaterally. Vaccination history included: Bnt162b2 (Dose 1 (five months postoperatively received first dose of the Pfizer vaccine), Anatomical location: Left shoulder). The following information was reported: CAPSULAR CONTRACTURE ASSOCIATED WITH BREAST IMPLANT (hospitalization, medically significant), outcome "unknown", described as "20 days after the second dose, seen to have a painful, distorted Baker IV capsular contracture"; LYMPHADENOPATHY (non-serious), outcome "unknown", described as "Six days after the second dose, she noted an enlarged lymph node in her left axilla"; HAEMATOMA (non-serious), outcome "unknown", described as "small delayed hematoma was the cause of the contracture"; BREAST SWELLING (non-serious), outcome "unknown", described as "Thirteen days after the second dose, she reported that her left breast was firm, swollen, and "tight".". Because of the severity of her symptoms, she underwent early revisional surgery with capsulectomy and implant exchange. Intraoperatively she was found to have an intact implant and a dense fibrotic capsule containing 37 cc of a thin reddish-brown fluid but no hematoma or organized blood clot. Although capsular contracture is typically thought of as a process that takes place over weeks to months, there is experimental evidence that provides a mechanism for capsular contracture evolving over only a few days, as seems to have occurred in this case. For example, tissue cultures obtained from the contracted capsules of women with silicone implants demonstrated the ability to induce a rapid upregulation of the genes for TGFB1, interleukin 8 as well as other inflammatory and profibrotic cytokines in vitro, which in turn, were thought to be responsible for the stimulation of contracture of fibroblast-populated collagen lattices over a 48- to 120-hour period. Another study also using tissue media derived from the capsules of women with implants showed enhanced T-cell proliferation and increased cytokine levels as compared to peripheral blood. These studies further support the concept of an immunologically mediated and rapid process for capsular contracture; the cellular composition of the capsule and the surrounding tissue seems poised to respond to an immunological stimulus. It is possible that the timing of the capsular contracture vis-a-vis the vaccine was a mere coincidence. The contracture occurred during the typical time frame for contracture (most are within the first year14), and it occurred following an operation (augmentation/mastopexy) that has a high contracture rate. In fact, the presence of a clearly hemorrhagic collection within the capsule raises an alternative hypothesis, that a small, delayed hematoma was the cause of the contracture. There are just over 30 case reports in the literature of hematomas occurring at least 6 months following cosmetic breast augmentation. Many of these had instigating events, such as trauma or physical strain or a recent iatrogenic coagulopathy, and many occurred in cases with aggressively textured implants, where the separation of the implant from the adherent capsule was thought to be the reason for the bleeding. This patient had none of these possible factors in her history. She denied trauma, was not engaged in implant displacement exercises or any kind of weightlifting, and her coagulation tests and platelet counts were normal. In delayed hematomas without a discernible etiology, the so-called called spontaneous cases, several authors suggest a variety of nonspecific inflammatory conditions as possible causes. Along these lines, the inflammatory response seen in a delayed hypersensitivity reaction (as in the aforementioned post-vaccine reactions to hyaluronic acid fillers) can induce angiogenesis and increased vascular permeability within days in animal models. Furthermore, the complex inflammatory and angiogenesis cascades share some of the same mediators, for example, TGFB1 and interleukin 820-22 and can be activated in concert. Therefore, the finding of a small amount of a bloody fluid in the capsule does not preclude an inflammatory, vaccine-induced mechanism for capsular contracture. Additionally, with the tight temporal sequence of events-the second dose of the vaccine, then lymph node enlargement, then a discernible tightening that rapidly progressed to a Baker IV contracture it seems hard to completely exculpate the vaccination as a possible cause, by one mechanism or another. It is also possible that the placement of the poly-4- hydroxybutyrate mesh in direct opposition to the implant contributed to the contracture, although the limited evidence that is available seems to suggest, if anything, that poly-4-hydroxybutyrate is more preventative than causative when it comes to capsular contracture. The ipsilaterally of the contracture to the vaccine site is also interesting; one might suspect that a systemic response to a vaccine would demonstrate no such side preference, although in this case there was an ipsilateral regional reaction with the enlarged lymph node. It would be premature to propose any protocol based upon a single case report. The pre-emptive use of zafirlukast has been suggested, for augmented patients getting the vaccine who experience any tightening, on at least 1 plastic surgical practice website and this makes sense from a mechanistic point of view. However, as a blanket recommendation for all augmented patients getting the vaccine, this would seem to treat many patients unnecessarily with a drug that is not entirely benign. Furthermore, even though zafirlukast acts upon a somewhat distal part of the immunological/inflammatory cascade (suppression of myofibroblasts), any interference with the body's immune response immediately after the vaccine might seem to be unwise and counterproductive to the entire point of the vaccine. The patient underwent the following laboratory tests and procedures: coagulation test: normal; platelet count: normal. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of capsular contracture associated with breast implant with early revisional surgery with capsulectomy and implant exchange and for breast swelling with montelukast.  No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information in the case, a contributory effect of the vaccine BNT162B2 to the reported events cannot be ruled out. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My lymph nodes on the left side (where I got my shot) started getting sore about 1-2 weeks after the second shot. It was painful to even keep my arm against my body. However, several days ago (4 months after the 2nd shot) the lymph node started getting sore again just like I'm August. Over the following few days the pain and soreness moved to the inner side of my arm, the bicep area, and continued to move down to my forearm (left side, where I received the shot). The arm was very sore to the touch and it was very painful to extend it - if I try to lift it shoulder-height or higher, it feels like the limb/muscle is being torn apart. The soreness was not caused by physical activity - I have not done any physical activity prior to the pain or since.  I've also started feeling a burning sensation on the left side of my torso - slightly below the top of the left rib cage. This pain was consistent for about a week straight and it started about 1-2 weeks after I received my 2nd shot. The pain/sensation still comes and goes on and off. I'm getting tests done to see what the issue it. I don't know if it was a side effect of the vaccine but the timing of it is concerning.

The injection was painless and I felt fine during the required 15 minute wait afterward. I went home and kept my activity pretty minimal for the rest of the afternoon. About 2.5 hours later, I was sitting at my desk watching a show when I started to feel a chill coming on, without necessarily being cold, and my teeth started to chatter. I was wearing a few layers of clothing, and the temperature of the house was at the usual 72 degrees.   This chill had happened with my previous two vaccine rounds, but not to the degree I was currently experiencing (I did not report the previous chill experiences because I thought that was to be an expected side effect). It?s still something that I knew what it was as soon as I felt it coming on.   So, as I?m continuing to shiver with my teeth chattering, I go to stand up and my muscles start to tense up. I was able to make it over to my bed and as soon as I laid down, the shivering & teeth chattering continued. And then my body went stick-straight as all my muscles tensed - I could not even move my arms to reach over to my cell phone, or to even hit the emergency SOS on my Apple Watch.  And while I live with a roommate, she was out for the evening, so I was completely alone in this, being unable to at the least even call for help. And I didn?t at the time even know how long this would last. Scariest moment of my life. The entire episode lasted maybe 30 minutes before I was able to move again.   Days later, I still have random sore spots in my body from that muscle tension. I?m a fairly fit guy (yoga teacher), so feeling this physically run-down a week later is unnerving.

PRIOR_VAX: I had minor chills with both initial Pfizer doses, progressively worse each time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 5:00pm, she became agitated.  She was screaming and saying she wanted to run away.  We kept her home.  Per doctor, administered additional doses  of peptide bpc-157, thc free cbd oil, took  an epsom salt bath, evening medications.  Felt better but had a hard time falling asleep.   Next day, seemed to be ok.  Administered morning medications and sent her off to school.  Arrived off bus a little down and not feeling well.  Over the course of the next few hours, she became agitated, raged, hit staff, screamed and yelled, tried to exit classroom.   She attends a therapeutic school with special education teachers.  They tried everything to get her to calm down, including restraint when she was hitting or trying to exit the building.  This went on for an hour and after 6 holds, the school called me.  Administrator informed me of situation and when i tried to talk to her on the phone, she screamed into it.  That was when everyone knew something was seriously wrong and they call 911.  She went to emergency room.  After a few hours she completely calmed down but due to the severity of the episode, the doctors wanted to keep her.  She was evaluated by a psychiatrist and was sent to inpatient hospital the next day due to bed unavailability.  She is now at streamwood behavioralhealth, arriving tuesday, 12/14/2021. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1st Event:  Blood started streaming from my nose while I was eating supper.  It drenched paper towel after paper towel in rapid succession. Went to bathroom to stand over sink while pinching the very end (soft part) of my nose.  Blood continued to come through my nose onto paper towel and back up in my nose and simultaneously stream from my mouth.  When I released my pinch to clear my nose, blood streamed out.  Early on, a large puddle the consistency of loose pudding came out and stayed in a large puddle in my sink.  It maintained it form w/o any slow seeping down the sink.  After 30 minutes approx. of blood streaming, I manage to call the 24-hour nurse who stayed on the phone with me for almost 2 1/2 hours until I could tell her the streaming might be very, very slightly slowing.  Meanwhile she was telling me I would have to go to medical facility if it didn't stop.  After 3 hours it did start to slow down though still flowing from my mouth and nose.  Finally it stopped and then I started passing very large clots from my mouth.  11:00 pm was when the last clot passed.  Total time from 5:30 pm until 11:00 pm.  2nd event was 11-19-21:  7:00 a.m. blood started drippin from my nose.  I pinched my nose and after about 4 minutes, it stopped.  3rd event was 12-1-21:  5.45 a.m.  I was lying in bed awake and all of a sudden I felt like I needed to blow my nose.  I got up and saw blood soaking my pillow, bed linens, etc.  This lasted until 9:00 a.m. when I passed the last clot through my mouth.  Bleeding streamed from before 5:45 a.m. until about 8:30 a.m.
LAB_DATA: Blood test after 3rd event -- 2 days after -- showed normal platelet level.

He requested a pop to which he was given a Coke. He then proceeded the vomit into the trash can while the pharmacist observed to make sure he did not have any further issues. The patient then stated after another minute that he felt much better. He continued to drink the Coke and was observed closely. After approx. 25 minutes he insisted he was feeling much better and wanted to leave  and was allowed to by the pharmacist. No further issues were reported.

Patient arrived to observation area. Observation team noticed redness on left ear, left neck, and left flank. Patient denied itching, pain, nausea, vomiting, and chest pain, but did say he had "slurred vision" explained as delayed tunnel vision. Patient and family communicated understanding and left the site in stable condition.

On 12/4/2021, 1 day after Moderna Covid-19 booster shot, patient developed decreased vision in the R eye. This progressed over the next 3 days to near complete loss of vision in the R eye. He was seen by an ophthalmologist on 12/7/2021 who recommended he start aspirin 81 mg PO daily & scheduled him for visual field & color plate testing in January 2022. With no change/improvement in vision, he went to a different ophthalmologist on 12/14/2021 for a 2nd opinion. B optic nerve edema was noted & findings concerning for R optic neuritis. He was sent to the ER for evaluation & was admitted to the hospitalist service.  He was seen by neurology, underwent MRI brain & MRV head. We were also concerned for optic neuritis. He was given a 3-day course of IV Solu-medrol 250 mg IV Q6 hrs. He has had significant improvement in his R eye vision & his ophthalmologic exam is also improved vs previous.  Vision is currently improved but is not back to normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got the vaccine on Saturday. I went to the gym for a spin after the vaccination. It was less than a half an hour. I was short of breath and couldn't complete the ride, very weak. I felt pain on the sides of my ribs...pleuritic pain. I went home and was tired. My resting heart rate on my watch which is typically between 55 and 64 went to 85-90 and did not go down until 10 days later but is still elevated. Achy low grade fever on Sunday. Went to work on Monday, tired, got an appointment Tuesday PM. EKG was abnormal and sent to ER. Cat scan multiple pulmonary embolisms both lobes and peripheral arterties. Hospitalized lots of pleuritic pain. Ulrasound of right leg DVT. Echo the next day...EF less than 30%. Hear Heart Failure in left ventricle. Started on blood thinner Lovenox 5 days. Prodaxa 2 tabs daily. Significant pleuritic pain persisted post hospitalization. Treatment for HF, Lisinopril 20 mgs, eventually on Beta blocker, Metropol Succinate started yesterday. I can do light exercise, heart rate still an issue, elevated. A little fatigued after exercise. The tx team at hospital including hematology  concluded that my pulmonary embolisms and HF is due to the vaccine. I am warned not to take another MRNA vaccine. The hope is that my condition will resolve in time. I was fit, 155 lbs, cycled about 2000-2500 miles a year. Road to work 8 months a year and on weekends. Exercised 6-7 times a week. Ski  in winter, rafted in summer. At this point I'm a little weaker, careful with exercise, need more layers to stay warm. Heart rate doesn't recover as quickly. My resting heart rate is elevated relative to baseline.
LAB_DATA: ER 11/23/21 EKG abnormal; CPR test negative; Cat Scan probably a dozen pulmonary embolisms.  In hospital 11/24/21 Echo...left ventricle EF <30% deemed heart failure; right ventricle fine, some inflammation on left. ??....These studies can be accessed through hospital medical record.
OTHER_MEDS: Dexadrine 5 mgs., Prilosec, Aleve, Mucinex-D.Vectical topical
CUR_ILL: Slight congestion, took rapid covid test--negative that day
HISTORY: Spinal stenosis, sciatica, hence Aleve, ADHD, psoriasis,

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Injection of vaccine immediately sharp pain, electric-like. Within 10 minutes of receiving vaccine, started to feel numbness, tingling in left hand/ forearm, and within 1 hour spread to left side of face, left arm, and left leg. The sensation symptoms ascended up the lateral aspect of my left arm axilla and spread to left chest (felt like left breast was completely numb). The lateral aspect of my neck, face, cheek, and eye proceeded to go numb/ lack of sensation. This all occurred within 1 hour of receiving the vaccine. It felt like a numbness and heaviness but no loss of motor function. Then within the following hour, it felt like pins and needles on the lateral aspect of my left foot. These symptoms fluctuated over the course of the following week, with the left lateral aspect of my foot and left hand symptoms persisting on/off. I had decreased temperature sensation on the left side of my body compared to the right within the first hour. Still able to feel pressure sensations at time of symptoms, but it was "off". The day following the first vaccine, woke up with persistent symptoms and additionally felt unwell/ flu-like. Next day symptoms included left-sided parathesias, dizziness, headache, nausea, body aches. The on/off left-sided parathesias and headaches continued for approximately 4 weeks. As a result of these symptoms, care was sought with Primary Care Provide on 1/15/21.  She recommended a neurologist. His examination on 1/21/21 showed "patchy loss to pinprick in her face, decreased pinprick in a left C8 and ulnar distribution, a possible T7 sensory level, gradient loss to vibration in both of her lower extremities, decreased pinprick on the lateral aspect of her left foot and heel...". His recommendation included a work-up to help rule-out other causes including a MRI of brain and spine with and without contrast, EMG, neuropathy labs. EMG from 2/11/21 was "unremarkable". MRI from 2/8/21 showed "possible thoracic AVM". Dr. recommendation was repeat imaging to diagnose spinal AVM. Care then sought out by patient at Medical Center due to insurance issues. Care established with Dr. via telehealth on 3/22/21. She recommended MRA of spine, performed on 5/15/21. MRA confirmed the possible spinal AVM. She recommended in person follow-up/ examination. At this time, I relocated, informed Dr. of this, and she recommended follow-up with Dr. at Medical Center. Care established with him 10/18/21. He recommended a spinal angiogram to confirm diagnosis of spinal AVM. This was performed on 12/14/21. Spinal Angiogram was negative for spinal AVM, and no determined cause for initial symptoms concluded.
LAB_DATA: In summary, 3 neurologist specialist visits with follow-ups, 1 MRI of brain/spine with and without contrast, 1 MRA of spine, 1 spinal angiogram, neuropathy labs, pre-op labs, and and EMG were performed since the initial symptoms/ vaccine. No determined connection with symptoms being related to anything besides the relation of them starting within minutes of the vaccine. MRI 2/8/21- possible spinal AVM. MRA 5/15/21- Possible spinal AVM. spinal angiogram 12/14/21- negative; neuropathy labs 1/23/21- negative; EMG 2/9/21- negative; preop labs 11/30/21 - unremarkable

I got my second Covid-19 Pfizer vaccine at 12:00pm on 12/16/21 in my left arm. Other than my arm being a bit sore, I had no other symptoms the rest of the day.  I woke up at 4:00am feeling like my body needed to stretch when my arms shot straight up, my legs straight down with my toes pointed, my chest and stomach twisted and pushed out, my lower back and butt twisted and pushed out the opposite way, and my body viciously shaking; it lasted 10-12 seconds and was extremely painful. I was half asleep and wasn?t sure what was happening, but my body was aching and I felt extremely exhausted; I wound up falling back asleep.  Two hours later I woke up again at 6:00am and the same exact thing happened again, I felt even more tired and my whole body hurt, I fell asleep again. I woke 30 minutes later (6:30am) to the same exact involuntary jerk of my arms going straight up, my legs pointing straight down, my torso contorted with my top half pushing out one way and my bottom half pushing out the opposite way and it was extremely, extremely painful, and my head was pounding. After that last involuntary convulsion I started having one every 5 minutes and I had no control over it. I started freaking out and was crying because it was so scary not to be able to control my body and being in so much pain. I thought I was going to have this condition for the rest of my life.  I called several friends who were nurses and then my doctor who told me if it doesn?t go away or slow down in a few hours to go to the immediate care. From 6:30 to 8:00am they went from every 5 minutes to every 10-15 minutes and went from being 10-12 seconds long to 3-4 seconds long. I was trying to control them and not do it but I had no control of my body. From 8:00am to 12:00pm I had one every hour. After 12:00pm they stopped. I never, ever, had anything like that happen to me in my entire life. I?ve never been so scared and gone through so much pain. It is now 12/19 and I haven?t had another convulsion. I still have a massive nonstop headache, my body still aches and it?s weird but my eyeballs hurt. It hurts to blink or close my eyes, it feels like I?m stretching my eyelid skin. I?m still extremely exhausted, fatigued, nauseous and I have no appetite. On 12/18 I woke up with my left armpit swollen the size of a baseball and it really hurts, it feels like it?s sore and bruised. It?s 12/19 and it hasn?t gone down at all.

This lasted for more than ten days and slowly after that got better, with me being able to walk little by little without a lot of pain in my foot.  My leg continues to be swollen, and I am still recovering from the adverse reaction to the vaccine.
CUR_ILL: Had been prescribed oral antibiotics, Clindamycin and Doxycycline, for a lower leg infection, right leg.  Completed full antibiotic treatment, leg in improved healing stage end of July, feeling well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after my booster, I had upper arm muscle pain as expected.  However I also had intense joint pain in the shoulder joint that radiated down my entire arm, limiting my range of motion and ability to lift / carry anything in that hand and arm.  This pain felt like a pinched nerve pain.  At the same time, pain also radiated into my upper left chest that felt muscular in nature, like a pulled muscle or something.  Neither was present before the booster and both developed the day after the booster.  All this lasted about a week before it improved any.  While it has mostly improved, even now, 2 months out from the booster, the shoulder joint pain, upper arm muscle pain, and chest muscle pain will recur occasionally at varying degrees of discomfort and I am certain it is booster related.  Again, none of this was present before the booster and was full onset the day after the booster.  I did not report this to my MD or to the Walgreens that administered the vaccine as I do not feel that either could do anything to remedy the issue.  Of note, the pharmacist that gave me the shot was very adamant about not using ice / ice pack to soothe the injection site of any discomfort because it would "ruin the shot."  This is in direct contrast to what I have since read about treatment of injection site discomfort.  But I followed her directions in case she knew something more than what I was reading about it.  I also do not expect the CDC to acknowledge this as a legit experience as the CDC has proven to not be very transparent, forthcoming, and reliable with the truth and is in the pocket of the liberal administration.  Also of note, I had "COVID arm" after the first vaccine, which I also reported.  It was in the same arm, my non-dominant arm.  My second shot was in the opposite arm as my first arm site was still recovering from COVID arm reaction to the first shot.  These reactions are in my opinion extreme and not natural.  I have had many vaccines in my life and never had anything like this.  2 out of the 3 COVID vaccines I have had, all Pfizer, created significant physical reactions to the injection arm that lingered for some time.  As far as I am concerned, this history of repeated adverse reactions exclude me from any future COVID vaccines or boosters because I cannot risk worsening reactions in the future.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12/7/21 - vomiting and nausea lasting 5 hours starting 8:30pm  12/8/21-12/9/21 constipation, loss of appetite , still nausea, excessive gas and bloat pain. bowel movements occur after honey water in night time. feels okay after.  12/10/21-12/12/2021 diarrhea starts once mild fever and nausea, 1 vomit leading to Er visit. 12/13/2021 - Findings:         Appendix: Perforated/infected: hole or blown-out tip and Abscess    Fluid amount: Diffuse (throughout the peritoneal cavity)    Fluid character: Thin serous/clear throughout, Fibrinopurulent/purulent localized to within right lower quadrant mesentery (contained abscess)    Other pertinent findings: distal small bowel obstruction due to fibrinous adhesions to proximal rectum/abscess cavity within distal small bowel mesentery.       Procedure in Detail: After informed consent was obtained the patient was transported to the OR. A timeout was performed and perioperative antibiotics were given. The patient was prepped and draped in the normal sterile fashion.   A 12mm port was inserted in the umbilical position under direct visualization and the abdomen was insufflated. A 5mm 30 degree laparoscope was introduced. Two additional ports were inserted, one in the suprapubic position and one in the left lower quadrant, under direct laparoscopic visualization without incident. There were numerous dilated small bowel loops with distally decompressed bowel loops as well as serous fluid throughout the peritoneal cavity, likely a reaction to the distal small bowel obstruction. The appendix was tucked under the distal ileal mesentery, where it had perforated, and upon mobilizing the distal ile um and its mesentery an abscess cavity was released, draining purulent fluid which was suctioned out. The appendix had a blown-out hole in its mid-body. The appendix was exposed and retracted anteriorly and inferiorly, splaying open the appendiceal mesentery. A window was made in the appendiceal mesentery with the Maryland ligasure cautery and then the appendiceal mesentery was then taken with the ligasure cautery. The base of the appendix was transected with an endoGIA stapler. The appendix was removed via the umbilical port site using a specimen retrieval bag and then the peritoneal cavity was suctioned out. The small bowel was run proximally starting at the terminal ileum, and some loose fibrinous adhesions from the small intestine to the proximal rectum/distal sigmoid were released bluntly. The transition point of the obstruction was positively identified and easily released. We ran the bowel proximally for several more feet, and there were no other points of obstruction. The bowel was still fairly dilated but was all viable.   Once this was completed the surgical bed was inspected and the staple line was noted to be intact and the hemostasis was adequate. A rectus sheath block was performed using 0.2% plain ropivacaine under laparoscopic visualization. The ports were removed under direct visualization and the abdomen was desufflated. The incisions were closed in layers with absorbable sutures, cleaned and dried, and sterile dressings were applied.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 3 weeks after my second vaccination,  I started having joint paint, starting in knees and fingers...the pain got worse and worse to where I couldn?t even walk up a flight of stairs or even tie my shoes.  I went to the doctor, had blood work drawn and they could see inflammation...I was put on prednisone.  They drew more blood and over the next month my pain grew worse to where nobody could even hug me.  I was then diagnosed with Lupus.  As the pain spread, my vision became blurry.  After a retina exam the doctor could see inflammation behind my eyes and I was sent to the Hospital...I was jaundice, developed kidney disease from the lupus, pancreatitis, and vasculitis all from the lupus.  My severe case put me in the ICU and I was hospitalized for almost a month.   I am now taking prednisone, hydroxychloroquine, Losartan, and I am currently receiving chemotherapy.  I?ve received chemo for the past three months, and I have three months to go, all to suppress my immune system that just would not calm down.   I am traveling two hours away for rheumatology, ophthalmology, and chemotherapy at hospital, and my vision has not returned completely all due to inflammation and overactive immune system.
LAB_DATA: Most mentioned above,  multiple CT scans, liver biopsies, kidney biopsies, and MRIs were also performed.
HISTORY: None at all before the vaccine, but have since been diagnosed with the autoimmune disease Lupus.  I was completely healthy before the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This mother was in good health at 38 weeks when she received her Moderna COVID19 booster (10 months after completion of her first two Moderna doses in January and February 2021.   Nine days later she had the onset of severe nausea, vomiting accompanied by upper abdominal pain.  She was evaluated and transferred to the hospital where she had an emergency cesarean birth of an ~ 8lb infant who had an initial APGAR or 3 but who eventually did well.   The peritoneal cavity was blood filled from a ruptured liver.  This required maternal ICU care and reoperation and an interventional radiology procedure to stem the bleeding. Multiple transfusions were required and this mother was eventually discharged at 10 days post op.   This mother had a family history of HELLP syndrome but she had not had this with her two previous pregnancies.  She did not have hypertension on initial evaluation.
LAB_DATA: Anemia and thrombocytopenia with elevated liver enzymes.

A couple of days later I developed Neuropathic Itch.  My body would get tingling and have goosebumps.  A part of my body would itch like crazy.  Then it would move to another part of my body.  The only part that does not itch is my head.  It quickly got progressively worse.  Doctors prescribed steroids, antihistamines, allergy medicines but nothing worked.  A family member who is a doctor suggested Lyrica.  I researched it and found out about Neuropathic Itch.  That was what I had.  My psychiatrist first prescribed 600 mg of gabapentin.  That was helping but not enough.  My regular doctor prescribed 1200 mg of gabapentin.   That allowed me to manage my pain and live life.  I started to get better and reduced to 900 mg.  But them on 11/24/21, I took a moderna booster and my itch rocketed back to where I was early at the height of the problem.   It became clear that my issue was caused by the Jansen injection on June 6, 2021.  I also have great pain in my wrists, but I do not know if that is involved.  It started 1 month after starting the gabapentin.  I am also getting a strange cough that started in the beginning of December.
