sudden severe hearing loss in right ear; This spontaneous case was reported by a non-health professional and describes the occurrence of SUDDEN HEARING LOSS (sudden severe hearing loss in right ear) in a 79-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 071F21A, 004M20A and 012L20A) for COVID-19 vaccination.     Concurrent medical conditions included Presbyacusis (moderate hearing loss bilateral due to age). Concomitant products included ALBUTEROL [SALBUTAMOL], FUROSEMIDE, LISINOPRIL, HYDROXYCHLOROQUINE SULFATE (PLAQUENIL [HYDROXYCHLOROQUINE SULFATE]), RIVAROXABAN (XARELTO), METOPROLOL and DILTIAZEM for an unknown indication.   On 14-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. On 11-Feb-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 01-Nov-2021, received third dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 03-Nov-2021,  after starting mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine), the patient experienced SUDDEN HEARING LOSS (sudden severe hearing loss in right ear) (seriousness criterion medically significant). The patient was treated with PREDNISONE (oral) for Hearing loss, at a dose of 1 dosage form. At the time of the report, SUDDEN HEARING LOSS (sudden severe hearing loss in right ear) had not resolved.            Patient take injectable steroid as a treatment drug on 2-Dec-2021. She takes lisinopril 20 mg twice daily. Patient take oral prednisone for two weeks. She went to her primary care doctor and was immediately referred to an Ear, nose, and throat specialist. The doctor said there was no guarantee and were hoping it was a viral thing and her hearing will come back. She had moderate hearing loss in both ears due to age but nothing like what was occurring.  Company comment included This case concerns a 79 year old female patient with medical history of Presbycusis - bilateral moderate hearing loss, who experienced the serious, unexpected event of sudden hearing loss 2 days after the third dose of mRNA 1273 vaccine. Patient had sudden severe hearing loss on the right ear, she was referred to an ENT specialist and was given 2 weeks of prednisone which did not relieve the symptoms. One month after the vaccine, she had an intratympanic steroid therapy on the affected ear. Doctor did not guarantee relief of symptoms, she has a hearing test scheduled and another follow up.  The patient's age and presbycusis remain as a confounders to the event.  The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA 1273 vaccine is not affected by this report.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns a 79 year old female patient with medical history of Presbycusis - bilateral moderate hearing loss, who experienced the serious, unexpected event of sudden hearing loss 2 days after the third dose of mRNA 1273 vaccine. On 14-MAR-2021, the patient was vaccinated with her first dose of tozinameran (COMIRNATY), lot# EN6207 (formulation, dose, expiration date, site of administration and route of administration were not reported) for prophylaxis. On 04-APR-2021, the patient was vaccinated with her second dose of tozinameran (COMIRNATY), lot# ER8729 (formulation, dose, expiration date, site of administration and route of administration were not reported) for prophylaxis. Guillian Barre Syndrome -- specifically AIDP superimposed on probable CIPD. Patient presented to ED with progressive bilateral upper extremity and lower extremity weakness. Symptoms began a few days after vaccination and progressed over months. Two weeks prior to admission, his bilateral lower extremity weakness acutely worsened to the point that he was unable to ascend stairs, prompting him to come to ED. Lumbar puncture was performed, revealing elevated protein and normal cell counts, consistent with clinical picture of Guillian Barre Syndrome. He currently remains in hospital and is undergoing IVIG infusions.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Two weeks after receiving the booster vaccine I developed hives.  They would pop up, be red, bumpy and itchy for about a half hour, then go away.  I went on steroids for 5 days, which made it good, but as soon as I came off of them, the hives were back.  I would have a flair up in the morning, be good at work all day, then they would come back out between 5:30 and 7:00 in the evening.  I was taking Benadryl to get through the night for a few weeks, then I went to my primary doctor on 12-14-21.  She advised me to switch to Zyrtec D, which has been amazing, for one week then come off of it, that would be today.  I have had some red splotches develop while on the Zyrtec, but it has not been itchy.  The reason I believe it may be from the booster shot, is because 3 other people in my office who received the booster on the same day are going through the same symptoms.

Patient was a 25 y/o female with no reported PMHx/PSHx. She was screened and vaccinated with 3rd dose of Pfizer Bio-N-Tech Vaccine at 0800. Patient was monitored in observation by a healthcare professional after receiving vaccine and became altered with uncontrolled, unilateral movement of the right side. Patient was assessed and brought to treatment care room within the clinic for further evaluation. Patient was assessed by APRN and nursing staff. Patient did not report loss of consciousness, loss of bowel/bladder function, and regained alertness and orientation within <15 secs of the event. Patient remained cognizant following the event and reported that she had a history of seizures but had not been diagnosed with seizures and did not take anti-epileptic medications. Patient stated that these symptoms do occur in rooms with larger crowds and stress. The patient noted that these events did not occur during her previous Pfizer vaccinations for Dose #1 and Dose #2. Patient also reported not having eaten since last night. Patient was assessed by healthcare staff on sight prior to release and vital signs were reassessed. MD was notified. Patient was instructed to follow-up with PCM for ongoing care management and to return to the nearest ER if symptoms worsened, persisted, or became more severe. Patient and husband were educated to return to the emergency room should any new symptoms including but not limited to chest pain, shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, or N/V develop. Patient and husband both vocalized understand and the patient was escorted home by her husband with stable vital signs.

For confirmation of diagnosis. Dr. was the one who told me I needed to report this. Within an hour of getting my second vaccine (Pfizer) my right eye started hurting. Vision started to get blurry, eye was red, and it was painful. I had my grandmother visiting at that time, and thought that maybe it had just been irritation from wearing contacts, so I unfortunately waited to see Dr.. When I finally saw Dr. he said it was Iritis, which is usually caused by an inflammatory disease. I have not been diagnosed with any inflammatory diseases. We attempted Prednisolone eye drops for a while and it didn't clear up the Iritis. Then he switched to Durezol and after a week or more the inflammation went away. I have not had any further issues related to my right eye or an Iritis inflammation since.
LAB_DATA: Dr. did tests on eye pressure, visual acuity, and took photos of the "snow" look in my eyes from the protein and inflammation in my right eye. He suggested that I get tested for HLA-B27.  I went to Dr. office and the test came out positive.

This is a 59y.o. male PMHx CABG 2019, MS, DMII, HTN, HLD, moderate persistent asthma, neuropathy presents with 1 day s/p seizure.  Patient was diagnosed with COVID 19 on 11/16/2021 and was at home recovering. Patient's granddaughter was having her online school lesson when she noticed her grandfather on the couch shaking uncontrollably.  The granddaughter, who is 7 years old, called her mother.  EMS was called and noted the patient to be postictal and confused. Patient presented to ED where he experienced another tonic-clonic seizure lasting about 30 seconds that was witnessed by EMS and nursing staff. Patient has no history of seizure disorder. Patient has had 2 follow-up visits with his PCP per curbside car visit.  The family have been concerned because the patient's POx was 88-90% RA and the patient was encouraged to present to the hospital, but refused. The PCP told the patient to follow-up in the office in a few weeks. Patient was fully vaccinated for COVID, but lapsed for the booster.     The patient is currently alert and states that he's been taking his Trulicity DMII medication as prescribed. The patient denies subjective fevers and chills. Patient denies tobacco dependence, no alcohol abuse, no drug abuse. Patient denies chest pain, no shortness of breath. Patient denies cough, no congestion. Patient denies abdominal pain. Patient endorses overall MS and osteoarthritic pain.
LAB_DATA: Patient tested positive for SARS CoV 2 at presentation. This is likely related to his previous Covid infection in November (patient had positive RT?PCR  The patient presented to the ED after having a witnessed tonic-clonic seizure. He had a second witnessed seizure while in the ED. CT head on arrival was negative for acute intracranial process. Lab work notable for glucose 875 (no acidosis), pseudohyponatremia of 123 (corrected 130's), creatinine 3.75, lactic acid 19.7, ammonia 94. COVID-19 test positive, but patient did have positive PCR on 11/16/21 and completed adequate 10-day isolation. He was started on IV fluids, given Keppra load and insulin, and admitted for neurology and nephrology consults. He had MRI brain that showed known multiple white matter foci related to MS with interval enlargement of focus within the right frontal lobe. He was continued on maintenance Keppra. His sugars improved with titration of insulin. Renal function also began to normalize near baseline. He was tolerating oral intake and ambulatory. He was stable for discharge on Keppra for outpatient follow-up with his neurologist. He was also instructed to monitor his sugars closely (daily) and keep a log for his PCP to review at follow-up.
OTHER_MEDS: Medication Administration Record reviewed. atorvastatin, 40 mg, Oral, Q HS carvedilol, 12.5 mg, Oral, BID cloNIDine, 0.2 mg, Oral, TID clopidogrel, 75 mg, Oral, DAILY docusate, 100 mg, Oral, BID ferrous sulfate, 325 mg, Oral, W/ BRKFST & DI

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When I woke up on 12/18/2021 (the day after my booster), I felt very fatigued. As the day went on I developed a very low-grade fever that lasted about 12-14 hours. I had developed a very large, red, swollen lump at the injection site (maybe 3" in diameter) that was very sore to the touch. As the day went on the discomfort at my injection site migrated into my arm and underarm area. The lymph node in my under arm area on my left side also felt swollen. I noticed that I lost some strength in my left arm due to the pain/swelling. Approximately 24 hours after my booster I did experience some body aches (mostly in my left arm and left side of my body). By 12/19/2021 most of the symptoms had subsided and the only remaining side effect was (and continues to be at the time of this submission) discomfort/pain at the injection site and my underarm area. It has decreased in intensity, but it still there.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About one week after receiving the Moderna booster I developed a case of dermatographia. At first I thought it was hives, as my father had recently tested positive for covid and developed hives a few days in. But after dealing with the issue for a few days I realized it wasn't occurring except where I was lightly brushed or scratched. It has continued with varied intensity since that date and persists today. If I scratch my skin lightly I will develop a welt along the scratch site within about five minutes. It becomes severely itchy and if left alone it will go away completely within about 30m to 1hr.  I have considered all environmental factors that could've changed during that time and have been able to rule them out through testing. At this time the only changes I know of that coincided with the onset of the dermatographia was the receipt of the booster a week prior and an exposure to covid a few days after the booster. I got covid tested starting on the exposure date and tested every couple of days for over a week. I have never tested positive for covid.
LAB_DATA: Negative covid tests throughout the time from the booster to now.
OTHER_MEDS: Advair 250/50 diskus, Albuterol Inhaler as needed, fluticasone propionate, buspar, zyrtec-d

My child started scratching and showed my some rashes on both sides of her temple and stomach Saturday evening (December 4, 2021).  I just monitored her during the night. By Sunday morning they disappeared. But by late Sunday evening (December 5,2021) I noticed her scratching her right arm, right leg, and stomach. When I looked she had red rashes on those locations that she was scratching. I took her to the ER around 11:00-12:00 am. She was seen by ER Dr., MD he observed the rashes and asked if she came into contact or had any new things to eat. I told him that she had taken the first shot of the pzfier covid vaccine on 11/30/2021. He said he could not state that it cause her mild allergy but he also said that he couldn't rule it out either since it was within less than a week since she took it. He said it was a mild reaction. He gave her benadryl and prelone. I asked if I should proceed with the second dose. He said I should and suggested that I follow up with our primary care doctor. I followed up with Dr. on Tuesday December 7, 2021. The rashes did not return and Dr. also advised that we continue with the second dose and that I report the incident. I reported it on the vaccine checkin via text message and received a call from the cdc (who suggested that I make a formal report online).
OTHER_MEDS: Flintstones Complete and Smarty Pants Kids formula multivitamin

He felt severe pain in chest and neck that night when he was lying down also had palpitations.  After the injection for the stress test, his blood pressure also went down but then improved.  He did not feel better so came and saw me on May 12, 2021.  I did follow-up testing due to ongoing low-grade fever and sharp chest pain which was positional.  Added CRP, sed rate and D-dimer again.  All of the markers were elevated including elevated myeloperoxidase antibodies elevated LDH, renal insufficiency with significantly elevated liver enzymes and significant anemia.  He was sent to emergency room when he was found to have pericarditis with pericardial effusion.  Was started on colchicine, prednisone and slowly improved. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had an advese reaction - stomach flu like with chills, vomiting and fever to 2nd Phizer injection in May that occured about 10 hours after the injection and  lasted 1 day followed by another couple days of weakness so, when mixing of vaccine types was allowed, I took advantage and switched to Johnson and Johnson.   At 10 PM, about 13 hours after the  J&J injection, I began to feel bad.  Severe chills began at 11 PM.  I was nauseous but went to sleep.  Around 2 AM on 11/16, my husband heard and felt me struggling.  I could not get my breath to speak.  It was as through my trachea was clogged with something.  He tried to sit me up, then flipped me on my stomach and began hitting my back because I was unable to tell him what was wrong.  Within less than a minute I began to be able to get some air, still struggling but could get air in and out.  Within 2 or 3 minutes I could talk again but was extremely weak for hours.  I did not go to the hospital because I was improving.  I did not report  this to anyone at the time.  My children encouraged me to report.  I have no long term effects and want to stay fully vaccinated.  I may, however, pay for an antibody test to learn if I need an additional booster before taking it in the event this is just a result of my antiboies fighting the vaccine, if that is possible?

This is a 72y.o. female with osteomyelitis on IV antibiotics, systolic heart failure (EF 20%), CAD, PAD, hypertension, COPD, and chronic kidney disease who presents from ECF complaining of increased fatigue and weakness. She also complains of dizziness, but notes she hasn't been out of bed in several days and denies any dizziness at rest. The patient was discharged to facility - on 11/19/21 on IV daptomycin and Rocephin. Prior to that admission, she had been ambulating with an assistive device. She denies any known fever and does not complain of back pain. No shortness of breath, cough, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, dysuria, flank pain, or diarrhea. She denies any known exposures. She believes she's been getting her IV antibiotics as prescribed and has not missed any doses.   In the ED, the patient was hypotensive with BP as low as 80/47. She was also febrile with a temperature of 102.2. SpO2 100% on room air. Labs notable for WBC 9.0, CRP 164 (elevated from 11.3 on 11/11), creatinine 1.22, hemoglobin 9.7 (reduce from 12.3 on 11/19). COVID-19, influenza, and RSV not detected. Urinalysis negative. Chest x-ray shows moderate cardiomegaly without pulmonary vascular congestion. She had CT L-spine that shows sequela of previously described osteomyelitis/discitis, stable compression deformity of L4, and multilevel extradural defects with associated degenerative changes creating up to moderate to severe spinal canal narrowing. Blood cultures were obtained. The patient's IV antibiotics were resumed. ID and neurosurgery were consulted.
LAB_DATA: Patient seen in follow-up for fever, and a previous diagnosis of L5-S1 discitis and vertebral osteomyelitis, receiving empiric outpatient abx coverage with dapto and ceftriaxone (cultures from CT guided biopsy were negative). Her PICC line was removed due to concern for this as a potential source, but both the cath tip and blood cultures from presentation have remained negative. Based upon this, repeat testing for COVID was performed with a positive repeat SARS CoV2 on 12/15. She was moved to appropriate isolation, and was treated with monoclonal Ab 12/15, which she appears to have tolerated well.  Today, she notes some mild fatigue but is otherwise doing well. Some mild lower thoracic back pain - "not the pain from my disc." Her supplemental 02 is back down to 2L NC with an O2 sat of 99%, and her temps have remained down (now on steroids for treatment of COVID).

On 12/7/2021, 4 hours after received first dose of Pfizer vaccine, I experienced heart palpitations (skipped beats) followed by a feeling of tightness and pressure in my chest which lasted several hours then would subside, then would return several hours later. This persisted for 3 days after which time I went to the Emergency Room on 12/11/2021 at 9:15am.  There I received an EKG and chest x-ray of which the results were normal. A blood test for Troponin was drawn at 9:43am with a result of 0.06 ng/mL which was flagged as High. I was put on a heart monitor under observation for 3 hours, after which time the blood test was repeated. The second troponin level was 0.01 ng/mL which was in the normal range. I was sent home and advised to follow up with Cardiology out-patient.  Unrelated, I had an appointment with my hematologist on 12/16 at which time he ordered a blood test for D-dimer to check for blood clots. The result was <0.19 mcg/mL which was in normal range.  On 12/17/2021 I had my follow up appointment with Cardiology. They performed an ECG the results of which were normal. Their thoughts were that I was low-risk and was not experiencing myocarditis, due to my normal results and low troponin. They scheduled at stress test for February. They did not advise against receiving my second dose of Pfizer.   The chest tightness and pressure began to diminish on 12/16, 9 days after receiving the vaccine. By 12/18, 11 days after receiving the vaccine, the symptoms were gone.

This dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine was administered to a 10y/o patient on 11/15/2021. The dose that was administered to the patient was of the 12y/o+ Pfizer formulation (purple cap). This was brought to our attention when the Department of Public Health sent a Immunization Registry (IR) line listing for this dose to our staff via email. The dose was entered under our organization's ID. DPH acknowledged that the lot number that was administered was of the 12y/o+ Pfizer formulation, but the patient was 10 y/o at the time of vaccination. We assessed our records and confirmed that this was the case. We reviewed CDC recommendations for an event of this nature and noticed that the recommendation is for the patient to receive their second as the 5y/o to 11y/o formulation at the regular 21-day interval. Per IR records, the patient received their second dose as the 5y/o to 11y/o formulation on 12/10/2021 at a different facility. Our staff contacted the patient's family yesterday and notified them of the error. The patient's family stated that the patient experienced normal side effects (headache, generalized body aches, injection site soreness) after the first dose, but these symptoms resolved after a few days. The patient is not currently experiencing any symptoms related to this event, but the patient's family was advised to follow up with the patient's primary healthcare provider in the event that any concerns develop in the future.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 2 weeks after receiving  my 2nd dose of Pfizer vaccine, my the top half of my right hand went numb. The numbness in my hand persisted for approximately 45 days before returning to normal.  The lack of strength in my right shoulder started to improve gradually after 45 days but continued to persist.  In October I injured the left shoulder in an accidental fall at my home while performing chores at a low height on a ladder.  I don't believe that this accident would have resulted in any significant injury had my shoulder be in its healthy, pre-vaccination condition,  as I was previously in a 6 days a week rotation of aerobic and strength training and was very physically fit in my upper body and shoulder area.  I continue to suffer from pain in my right shoulder.  I have received a steroid injection and numerous physical therapy sessions for this health issue.

Patient fully vaccinated including booster.  COVID testing however in the emergency department was positive.  Chest x-rays done in the emergency department on 12/12/2021 which showed minor atelectasis or opacity of the left lung base.  All other infectious workup remained negative during this admission. Patient was given monoclonal antibody in the emergency department however despite requiring no supplemental oxygen, patient was admitted for further evaluation and treatment of patient's shortness of breath because after receiving monoclonal antibody, patient subsequently became severely hypertensive, short of breath and had wheezing.  Following this reaction, patient was given albuterol, dexamethasone and Benadryl for possible reaction.  Chest x-ray was repeated at that time to ensure no pulmonary edema and this was negative and stable compared to previous chest x-ray.  Patient was given remdesivir and dexamethasone in emergency department and throughout the duration of this admission (two doses of remdesivir given).  Patient continued to remain on room air and having completely recovered from suspected reaction, it was determined clinically stable to discharge home off antibiotics or steroids per my discussion with Dr.  Patient continued to eat, drink, void and ambulate on his own during this admission as per home baseline.  Patient eager to discharge home today though did have significant concerns about infecting his wife.  We did discuss safety measures and quarantine recommendations at great length.  Patient is aware that he may not present back to our office until 10 days of quarantine has elapsed but should call with questions/concerns.  We are pushing his chemotherapy out until 12/22/21. During this admission, patient was evaluated by the physical therapy team and felt that patient was stable to return home with outpatient services. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The nurse gave me an injection into my left deltoid but after pushing the syringe and removing the needle she stated "I'm unsure if I had any vaccine in that shot.  No I'm almost positive I didn't have any, it just didn't push right. Oh well, we will just give you another one."  I asked if she was sure in which she stated "yes I'm fairly certain I didn't have any vaccine in there.  You only got this much (pointing to the syringe) of air so it will be fine.  We will just give you another one."  I asked if she was sure that that would be ok, in case I did get vaccine in the injection.  She reassured me again and stated that it would be fine.  On Monday evening I felt "off" and felt like my heart was beating faster than normal but went to bed.  In the morning I felt better so went to the gym as I do most days of the week at 5am.  During class I felt a slight burn in my chest but it went away fairly quickly.  On the way home from the gym I noticed that my heart rate was note returning to baseline as quickly as it normally would and noticed on my apple watch that my HR was between 120-130bpm.  I started feeling sick and dizzy and got really sweaty.  I also started to feel like I was going to pass out so I pulled over and called my husband for reassurance.  During our phone call I felt sick and ended up throwing up.  Afterwards I started to feel well enough to drive the rest of the way home.  While getting ready for work I noticed that my heart rate was still above it's normal and was between 100-120bpm.  I called my local PCP who recommended that I present to the ER.  While at the ER my heart rate was slowly returning to baseline.  No abnormalities were observed on the EKG and all labs were normal except an elevated troponin of 50.  Due to the elevated troponin I was admitted to the hospital for observation and was in the hospital from 12/14-12/16.  My discharge diagnosis was Minoca and I am still undergoing testing.
LAB_DATA: Troponin every 3 hours throughout hospital stay. (Last value was 444); Telemetry monitoring (12/14-12/16); ECHO 12/15; cardiac MRI 12/15; EKG 12/14 & 12/15; angiogram 12/16; zio patch placed 12/20 and will be removed on 1/3/22.  There were multiple other lab tests ran throughout my hospital stay.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Earlier in the week, I tweaked my back.  That day and every day up and including my Moderna vaccine booster I was well on my way to recovering from sciatica.  In fact, I needed no pain meds and only took Tylenol and Advil while continuing to walk several miles per day, doing 80-100 bodyweight squats (full range of motion), and doing pilates work on a reformer.  Thursday after the shot, I barely could get out of bed and I couldn't walk very far without assistance.  By Saturday I could not sleep because of the pain.  Sunday, I was in such bad shape that I laid on the floor of the bathroom for 5 hours finally giving up and calling the ambulance.  At the ER I had a dozen or so rescue doses of Fentanyl, Morphine, and Valium.  None of them took away the pain.  I didn't sleep that night and I was unable to get an MRI unless sedated.  Finally, by Tuesday I slept and the pain decreased.  I feel that I'm well on my way to recovery but I've never experienced such pain and I have been stabbed, shot, broken bones, knocked out, 2 back surgeries, and 3 sinus surgeries.
LAB_DATA: There are no laboratory results other than I do and have had a herniated disc in L5, but I'm stating that the pain that was associated with it is well out of proportion.  I've had sciatica before and this was much worse.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt sent letter to pharmacy stating: I am 65 years old.  I was given an Influenza Virus Vaccine October 6, 2021 by a staff member in your pharmacy.  I've had several flu vaccines throughout the years, and other than a bit of tenderness at the injection site, I've never had an issue whatsoever.  This time I did.  The person administering the vaccination gave me the injection, and although the injection itself was painful, I didn't think anything of it.  The employee told me to remain for 15 minutes in case of a reaction of some sort.  I agreed but told her I had some shopping to do that would take at least that long.  Before leaving the store, I did notice my arm was in pain, but recalled other friends have told me their flu shots were painful, and in some cases lasted a week or so.  My arm has remained in pain since that day.  I am an avid workout individual, and every active person.  My left arm is limited in performing everyday functions, such as attaching my seatbelt, carrying my 2 year old granddaughter, putting on clothes, working out, and reaching to some length.  the pain even affects my sleeping.  Since October 6th, I have not had a complete night of sleep.  I did finally perform an internet search and found that my shot could have been given with a larger needle than my small frame can handle.  Another article mentioned a flu vaccine could cause a type of pre-arthritis.  Anyway, I did finally see a doctor today (pt's letter was dated 11-29-21 and received by pharmacy 12/20/21) and she is treating me with a drug for possible inflammation and muscle relaxer to help me sleep.  I know I possibly should have notified you earlier, but I continue to believe the pain would eventually subside, and I'm certainly hoping it does now that I have medication.  I'm notifying you at the request of my doctor.  She believes, if it's possible the pain is directly from the vaccination, then it's vital that I notify you, so that this does not happen again.  I know I will certain be asking more questions about needle size etc before getting another vaccine of any sort.
COVID-19 Vaccine, Pfizer BioNTech is administered after its useful life. Shelf Life Date 11/17/2021 7:00am

About 8 days after my Covid booster, and 1 day after I got my flu shot, I developed a red, painful, severely itchy rash with hives over most of my body. It severely disrupted my sleep and my ability to  work and perform basic life functions. I waited a few days in hopes it would resolve, but it got worse. I called my GP and got a course of oral steroids (prednisone). This brought down the severity somewhat, but the rash continued. I sought out my dermatologist (I do have chronic eczema) and he stated he?s had at least one other patient develop the same thing about a week post-Covid booster. He told me to start taking my Zyrtec twice a day (I?ve been taking it once a day for years) and to use a pain/itch-relieving OTC lotion. That has been working well so far but the rash is still present and still flares up from time to time.
LAB_DATA: Dermatologist (Dr. took blood in the week of November 29, 2021 (approx) and found that I was in the low positive range for an autoimmune condition. He stated that it was most likely due to the booster and noted that the same thing had happened to at least one other patient of his.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalized (11.23.21);  COVID-19 positive (11.16 and 12.13.21);  fully vaccinated  Admission Date: 11/23/2021 Discharge Date: 12/13/2021  DISCHARGE DISPOSITION: Subacute rehab HOSPITAL COURSE : 59 yo male with history of MS, chronic HFpEF, HLD, and recent COVID-19 who presented to the ED with expressive aphasia first noted 11/23 (1800). As baseline, spouse reported patient to be conversant.  In the ED patient noted to be mildly tachycardic with tachypnea. Initial lab work demonstrated an AKI. Stroke code was initiated with CT head, CTA head/neck and CT perfusion scan unremarkable. Neurology was contacted by ED and recommended admission to the medicine service for MRI. # Toxic/Metabolic Encephalopathy  # Early Onset Dementia In Setting of MS MRI brain w/ and w/o contrast (11/24) without acute findings, and notable for global atrophy and sequelae of chronic MS. 2 hour EEG (11/24) without epileptiform activity. UA without evidence of infection and VBG without Co2 retention. Neurology signed off given lack of stroke and/or seizure findings. Etiology felt secondary to progression of dementia and/or COVID-19 PNA. On 11/30 stroke code was called overnight due to increase in expressive aphasia and generalized weakness, head CT without bleed and neurology re-evaluated patient and felt no neurological deficits and therefore signed off.  # Bilateral Pulmonary Embolism with Acute LLE DVT Left lower extremity venous US (11/25) with extensive VTE extending to the common femoral vein. CTA thorax (11/25) with bilateral PE with at least moderate clot burden and no evidence of heart strain. Echo obtained and confirmed lack of heart strain. Etiology felt secondary to COVID-19 and initially given dose of Apixaban in the ED, with heparin gtt while hospitalized. IR was consulted and felt no intervention needed for PE. CT abd/pelvis (11/25) was obtained to determine extent of LLE DVT which showed IVC to be patent and no evidence of extension superior to left inguinal region and therefore IR recommended no intervention regarding DVT. However, IR placed an IVC filter.  # Right Iliopsoas Retroperitoneal Hematoma Patient was noted to have down trending Hgb and therefore GI was consulted with recommendation for CT abd/pelvis w/o contrast due to AKI. Imaging revealed retroperitoneal hematoma for which IR was consulted. As hemoglobin remained stable, recommending monitoring closely while on heparin gtt.  He was subsequently switched to Eliquis which he tolerated well.  CT abd/pelvis w/o contrast was repeated on 11/30 with stable hematoma, the hemoglobin was monitored and remained stable.. COVID-19 PNA with Acute Hypoxic Respiratory Insufficiency Patient was initially diagnosed with PCR (11/15) and fully vaccinated x2 with Moderna (albeit >6 months ago). CTA thorax demonstrated mild-moderate GGO. Strep pneumonia and legionella testing was negative. Complete 1.5 gm of Azithromycin for atypical coverage and 5 days of IV Rocephin for typical coverage while hospitalized. He was also treated with Decadron during hospitalization. Resp failure worsened on 12/1. CXR updated. Unasyn added. Blood cx sent (for fever).  Infection was controlled under Unasyn was discontinued.   His hemoglobin remained stable. While on steroids he was noted to have high blood sugars.  His hemoglobin A1 c was 6.3.  He required insulin during hospitalization.  He was subsequently discharged on metformin.  The patient the was continued on tapering dose of prednisone.  He will subsequently go back to his usual dose of prednisone of 2 mg. The patient noted to have malnutrition.  He failed the swallowing study.  Patient's wife agreed for PEG tube placement and tube feedings. The patient had a tube placed and was started on tube feeding which he tolerated well.  He was subsequently discharged to subacute rehab

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is deceased (12.10.21); hospitalized (11.29.21); COVID-19 positive;  fully vaccinated  Admission Date: 11/29/2021 Discharge Date: 12/09/2021 DISCHARGE DIAGNOSES 1. Atrial fibrillation with RVR 2. Bilateral pulmonary emboli 3. Altered Mental Status 4. COVID-19 5. E coli UTI 6. Left distal femur fracture s/p ORIF  7. Acute on chronic macrocytic anemia 8. Dysphagia 9. Hypertension 10. Type 2 diabetes 11. BPH 12. GERD 13. Hx gout 14. Sensorineural hearing loss DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: HOSPITAL COURSE:   Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response Patient was admitted to the hospital from his nursing home in AFib with RVR.  This required a Cardizem drip in the intensive care unit.  Echo showed EF of 50%.  This was transitioned to Cardizem 360 mg long-acting and 50 mg metoprolol long-acting.  If transition to hospice was not made, he would have required additional rate control medications. Bilateral pulmonary emboli On CT angiogram in the emergency department, bilateral pulmonary emboli were seen.  He was started on therapeutic Lovenox, which was transition to Eliquis.  This was likely a provoked PE secondary to being nonweightbearing after recent ORIF of left distal femur fracture on 11/13. COVID-19 Patient became hypoxic during his stay requiring briefly 1 L of oxygen.  COVID testing was completed which was positive.  Patient was placed in isolation and started on Decadron. Urinary tract infection Upon chart review, patient had a positive urinalysis with a culture growing E coli couple days prior to admission.  This does not appear to have been treated and patient was treated with a course of Keflex.  Over the course of his stay, his condition deteriorated. He did try to get out of bed on his own and fell 12/7, CT head negative for intracranial process; no other injuries sustained. Xray of surgical site left hip negative for new fracture.  He was A&O x0 yesterday morning.  Hospice meeting was held yesterday at noon with patient's son/DPOA and patient was transitioned to hospice upon discharge.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I don?t remember everything that happened because it was several months ago. I do remember getting tingly limbs and almost immediately after getting the vaccine having brain fog. Not being able to think as clearly as before, feeling dumber. This lasted for a while, probably weeks. I felt like the vaccine messed with my nerves. I was so worried about these effects that I made an appt with my doctor. I think the appt was made a few days after I was vaccinated. I had been seeing doctor. I received my vaccine elsewhere. I felt as though I had cold or hot water being poured down my legs. Even though that wasn?t happening. If you message Mardi, she could probably look up exactly what I experienced in more detail. She told me that because I had experienced some of these feelings before that I was probably okay. I had experienced prior to my vaccine feeling a wet spot on my leg when there was no water there, but nothing like this. Before the vaccine the wet spot feeling would be infrequent, happening every great once in a while. Maybe once a week or less. This was much more intense , after the vaccine, and it came and went often throughout the day. I would get the feeling of water being poured down my legs several times a day after getting the vaccine. I think this lasted for a couple of weeks. I don?t remember if it felt like it was hot or cold water, but it was one of those. I would be interested to know if anyone else had experienced these problems with the covid vaccine and if they went on to get a second dose of the moderna covid 19 vaccine, safely, or if the CDC recommends I do not pursue getting fully vaccinated because of the adverse side effects I experienced from the first vaccine dose. Please let me know what you think I should do.  I feel like after a few weeks or months, I felt better again. Just those few weeks right after, I had a lot of crazy symptoms of things I had never experienced before.
LAB_DATA: I do not think the doctor ordered any further tests

Hospitalized (12.12.21 - still admitted); COVID-19 positive (12.13.21); fully vaccinated  On Admission:   Brief History and Medical Decision Making:  Patient is a 55 yrs female who is admitted with altered mental status likely secondary to multifactorial etiology.  Patient has a history of multiple sclerosis with bilateral lower extremity weakness and has a known cognitive decline.  Patient resides at a nursing facility.  She tested positive for COVID-19 pneumonia few days ago.  Patient was reportedly not taking her medications at the facility and was nauseated.  She developed altered mental status and fever which prompted her to be evaluated at the emergency department.  As per chart review patient with known cognitive decline however is oriented x4 at baseline. On admission CT head was done which was negative.  Chest x-ray showed bilateral pneumonia.  Labs showed hyponatremia with sodium 150. Patient's UA was positive for urinary tract infection.  Rocephin, azithromycin And vancomycin likely for community-acquired pneumonia and urinary tract infection.  Will continue with IV Rocephin for urinary tract infection at this time.  Patient currently on room air.  Received 1 dose of dexamethasone 6 mg IV for COVID-19 pneumonia treatment. Patient's altered mental status likely secondary to dehydration from COVID-19 infection and urinary tract infection.  Sodium levels improving with D5W infusion.  Will continue to monitor BMP and discontinue D5W 1 sodium levels within normal range.  Continue with IV Rocephin for urinary tract infection.  Will follow-up urine culture results and blood cultures.  Continue dexamethasone for COVID-19. Progress Note from 12.21.21: CHIEF COMPLAINT: Encephalopathy ASSESSMENT / PLAN: Principal Problem:   Encephalopathy Acute metabolic encephalopathy- improving Chronic encephalopathy secondary to MS and/or microvascular dementia - CT head negative for acute changes in ER - Etiology of acute worsening likely secondary to electrolyte abnormalities and infection. Meningitis suspected - MRI brain obtained due to hx of MS, showing no acute ischemic infarction, altho intracranial volume loss greater than expected for age, and T2 hyperintensity within supratentorial white matter possibly related to MS versus chronic microvascular changes. Discussed with Neurology and MRI appears stable with no concern for MS flare.  - Neurology consulted, recommend continuing empiric antibiotics for meningitis at this time, but no indication for LP given that patient is improving and that daughter states she usually becomes confused like this when she is ill.  -Continue ceftriaxone/ampicillin for 10 day course, and vancomycin for total 7 days (ends after today). Day 7/10 abx today - gabapentin and norco resumed (for PN) -psych states no apparent psychiatric pathology Dysphagia-oropharyngeal - barium swallow 12/20/21-pt unable/unwilling to swallow contrast.  -Corpak placed 12/20/21-pt dislikes it, needs wrist restraints.  COVID 19 PNA-resolved CXR bilateral COVID 19 PNA Tested Positive 12/8/21 Remains on room air.  Did not qualify for monoclonal antibodies. Consider starting decadron and remdesivir if patient becomes hypoxic and requires oxygen. AC on eliquis Supportive care

On June 22, 2021 I began having pain in my lower right back underneath my armpit. Over the course of the next 24 hours, the pain worsened and I was unable to lay down, had trouble breathing and was sweating profusely. Throughout the day on June 23, I completed a telehealth and urgent care visit where I was (incorrectly) diagnosed with bronchitis. My symptoms worsened that evening and I went to the ER. After a series of tests, I was diagnosed with a pulmonary embolism (PE). I was hospitalized overnight and discharged the next evening. I had no known risk factors for PE. In August I was referred to a hematologist and went through a series of blood tests, which I will outline in the next question, over the course of three months. On November 29, I received a diagnosis of antiphospholipid syndrome (APS). I have had no history of autoimmune disorder, ongoing health issues or clotting. I wanted to report this due to the proximity to my COVID-19 vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: History obtained from: patient History limited by: mild confusion   Chief Complaint: Seizure   HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS   a 49 y.o. female who presents to the Emergency Department complaining of seizure onset prior to arrival.    Per Nurse, the patient had a headache and vomiting all day. Patient was given Zofran in the hallway for nausea. Patient was post-ictal upon EMS arrival. Patient has never had a seizure before.    Per Husband, the patient has had a headache and has been vomiting all day. Patient states that her frontal headache got worse throughout the day. Patient was found on the bed, shaking, stiff, and eyes had rolled back for about 5 minutes. Husband states that she returned back to baseline in 5 minutes. Patient states that she bit her lip. Patient mentions that she never gets migraines. Patient reports photophobia, sound sensitivity, and feeling of being hot and cold throughout the day. Husband states that she has her Covid-19 vaccinations. Husband also mentions that she has been using Pepto Bismol throughout the day without relief. Patient denies vision loss, difficulty swallowing, one-sided weakness/numbness, neck stiffness/pain, nasal congestion, abdominal pain, dysuria, hematuria, hematochezia, and any sick contacts.    Caveat: Full history of present illness is unobtainable from patient secondary to mild confusion  Chief Complaint:  Seizure, confusion 49 y.o. female with a history of tobacco abuse who presents with new onset seizures.  History as per EMR and as per patient's mother with home I spoke on the telephone.  Patient was apparently complaining of a headache all throughout the day, had multiple episodes of nonbloody and nonbilious emesis at home.  She then had 1 episode of seizure at home which lasted for a few minutes, she bit her lip during this episode.  She returned to baseline mental status in about 5 minutes.  Patient's mother tells me that she does not use any illicit drugs, but smokes marijuana occasionally.  She drinks alcohol socially, has not had any history of seizures in the past.  Her mother does not recollect any recent changes to her lifestyle in the past few days except that she received her Johnson & Johnson COVID-19 vaccine about 2 weeks ago.     Patient came to the ED, while in the waiting room, she had another episode of witnessed seizure that lasted a few seconds. She was then brought back into her room in the ED and had yet another episode of seizure, was given Ativan and 1000 mg IV Keppra.  Admitted for further management.   COVID-19 vaccination status:  Vaccinated (J and J), yet to receive booster. COVID-19 test:  Negative today.     Chief Complaint:  New onset seizures   History of Present Illness:    History was obtained from a review of the electronic record and discussion with the patient . 49 y.o. female who presented to the ER on 12/20/2021 after having new onset seizure.  The patient has been vomiting with the headache.  Her boyfriend witnessed her having seizure which lasted for a few seconds.  After presenting to the hospital, patient had a CT brain which was negative for any acute abnormality.  The patient had another witnessed seizure for which she was started on Keppra.  She was admitted to the hospital, neurology evaluated the patient at bedside.  She was feeling better.  She denied any acute symptoms.  The patient does not recall much of the events from yesterday.  She denies any previous history of seizures or any family history of seizures.  She did have a tongue bite from the seizure.  Her urinalysis was positive for fentanyl and cannabinoids.  She does admit to drinking alcohol twice weekly.  Assessment and Plan:   1)  new onset seizure, etiology unclear, possibly provoked from underlying polysubstance abuse Recommendations:  -continue Keppra 500 mg twice daily -MRI brain without contrast pending to evaluate for any structural abnormality -EEG currently pending Per DMV law: Patient is advised to not drive motorized or nonmotorized vehicle for 6 months since last seizure or loss of consciousness event. Do not engage in heavy machinery work, taking bath or swimming unsupervised to ensure your safety.  -If patient has a seizure which lasts more the 5 minutes, three consecutive seizures without recovery between seizures, or has injury during seizure, please take patient to the emergency department; if the patient has any respiratory distress due to seizure, please place patient on his/her side and call 911 -patient can follow up in Neurology clinic for next available appointment, please call Neurology for any questions

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started off sneezing like crazy, uncontrollable. Saturday, throat was itchy. By later that night into Sunday morning, I was in full blown chills, cough, freezing cold. I didn't want to get out of bed, and I just did not feel good. Monday, I got up and went to work, I still wasn't feeling well and went to the doctor's office. By this time, I had mucus and everything else. I couldn't breathe. I had to sleep sitting up because if I laid down, I would cough and felt like I was being suffocated. So I went to the doctor that Monday and was prescribed Promethazine. So, I got up on Tuesday, I felt at my worst so I couldn't go to work. I worked from home, and I just had really bad congestion and cough. Cough was worse than what it originally was. Called the doctor and asked maybe they need to do a chest x-ray. The x-ray was clear, and it was within normal limits. I stayed home on Wednesday and went to work Thursday, still had the congestion and cough even with the medication. Every day I went to Starbucks to get a medicine ball to help with the symptoms, but cough is still consistent every hour. Even with taking the medication. In the hour, I cough every 10 - 15 minutes and it's like a strangling feeling. I do feel a little better but still ongoing coughing.
OTHER_MEDS: Aspirin 81mg; Atenolol 25mg; Research study medication - Mavacamten
ALLERGIES: Codeine; Robaxin; Methocarbamol - Causes brain tumors

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Beginning on Dec 13th, I experienced what appeared to be hives on my skin. They were very itchy and would appear and disappear randomly all over my body all throughout the day. I had never before experienced hives or any allergic reaction to anything. I had not recently tried any new foods or new medications. I sought help for the hives and was prescribed prednisone and loratidine, and I took Benadryl as well because the hives would only improve with Benadryl. I later returned to the doctor as I was experiencing side effects from the medications and my hives were not improving. The most concerning symptom that caused me to return to the doctor was a symmetric sharp pain in my hands that was otherwise unexplained and caused me to have difficulty doing my regular daily activities that required my hands. I was then also prescribed Pepsid and the prednisone was decreased. As of Dec 21 2021, I am still experiencing hives, although they are much less itchy than before. These hives very much disrupted my schoolwork and caused me to require special accommodations for some of my final exams.

I went to see my PCP and she sent me home to rest. The next day it got worse, and I was vomiting, and I couldn't sit up and I couldn't hear (I'm hearing-impaired) so I was sent to the ER. Moving my head was extremely painful. I was sent to a neurologist who confirmed I had a leak of cerebrospinal fluid that was coincidentally and "spontaneous" leak of the fluid after my vaccination. The MRI scan confirmed it and tried to find the source of the leak. Since my brain was resting on so many nerves, I was suffering from vomiting, nausea, vertigo, distorted my hearing, couldn't talk, or walk normal during that time. I was sent home from the ER that same day. I was just informed to receive bed rest by laying my head flat.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the Janssen COVID-19 vaccine (batch/lot# 1855191 and expiration date:  04/11/2021), at 10:48 pm in error. He was due for second dose Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. Patient verbalized his request to receive the Janssen dose. The RN/vaccinator gave him the Janssen COVID-19 vaccine. The immunization registry staff brought this to the attention of the lead RN vaccinator after the dose was given. They did not disclose problem until after incident had occurred. Lead RN vaccinator provided education on the importance of verifying doses before administration occurs. Everyone verbalized understanding. Earlier in the day the resource nurse provided a list of clients that needed the COVID-19 vaccine, however this patient was placed on the Janssen COVID-19 vaccine list rather than the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine list. Lead RN vaccinator discussed error with the nurse. During the discussion there was no other evidence of a second dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine given prior to today's Janssen COVID-19 vaccine. Resource nurse verbalized understanding of error displayed on the list given. Lead RN made supervisors aware of incident, no further direction needed at this time. Observation period done. No complaints from patient or via staff.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 11/1/2021, I received the Moderna Covid-19 booster in my left arm. This was my 3rd dose of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine. On 11/13/2021, I woke up to a red rash on each of my upper hamstrings/lower buttocks. As the day went on , I proceeded to develop hives and a red rash on my scalp, neck, and shoulder areas. I also have slight swelling of the eyelids. On 11/15/2021, my dermatologist diagnosed me with urticaria as a result of the Moderna Covid-19 booster. I was prescribed 20 mg of Zyrtec and 10 mg of Montelukast in the morning and 10 mg of Benadryl in the evening. This helped alleviate some of the itchiness, but the redness persisted. On 12/3/2021, during a follow-up visit with my dermatologist, I was diagnosed with dermatographia as a result of the Moderna Covid-19 booster. My medication was adjusted to 20 mg of Zyrtec and 10 mg of Montelukast in the morning and 10 mg of Allegra at night. While the itchiness and rash is manageable with the use of antihistamines, the dermatographia persists as of the date of this writing.
LAB_DATA: Dermatologist observed my hives and rash on my first visit to his office and after asking me questions, concluded that the condition was urticaria caused by the Moderna Covid-19 booster. At my follow-up appointment, the dermatologist observed red marks on my legs and in photos I showed him of my trunk and suspected dermatographia may be the cause. He proceeded to then draw an "X" on my back to see if a red, swollen line or welt appeared in the shape of an "X", which it did a few minutes later. I was then diagnosed with dermatographia due to the Moderna Covid-19 booster.

Chest tightness and anxiety centered around the heart lasted from October 1, 2021-October 19, 2021. The sensation presented as a constant, low-grade sensation of chest tightness and anxiety from when I woke up until I fell asleep. I experienced nightmares almost every night. The sensations of chest tightness and anxiety did not inhibit me from working or going about my day, despite the fact that I felt both constantly. The sensations stopped on October 19 when I got my second Moderna dose (lot #011F21a ). I experienced a fever, chills, headache, and tiredness on October 19-20, 2021, but I didn't feel any chest tightness or anxiety on those days. The sensations of chest tightness and anxiety started again on October 22, 2021 and lasted until October 26, 2021. They recurred November 14-17, 2021, December 2-4, 2021, and December 16-18, 2021. My pulse and blood pressure, when measured during these periods, have been normal. I discussed these symptoms with my practitioner on November 4, 2021 as part of my physical exam. Dr. gave me an EKG and a GAD-7(generalized anxiety disorder) assessment . After the EKG showed nothing and I scored a 3 on the GAD-7, Dr. "reassured patient that his chest tightness was likely secondary to anxiety" and he "advised patient that his anxiety may have been cyclical and worsening due to his chest tightness (which was likely secondary to his anxiety." I declined a referral to a psychologist and agreed to follow-up with Dr. in 6 months or earlier if conditions worsened.  Since November 4 my conditions  haven't worsened, but they have recurred on November 14-17, December 2-4, and December 16-18. Until I took the Moderna shots, I had absolutely no history of anxiety or chest tightness whatsoever, and no history of any kind of mental disorders. I've had no history of any health problems of any kind until this.
LAB_DATA: EKG and GAD-7 on November 4, 2021.  The EKG was "normal" and I scored a 3 on the GAD-7.

First 8 hours (April 8 and 9th, 2021) I  became extremely nauseous, and vomited on and off for the next  48 hours. First 24 hours (April 9, 2021) Fever, chills, sweating. First month: By May 2021 I quit my internship because I stayed nauseous and had really bad headaches, along with uncontrollable crying and anxiety. I had depression and extreme fatigue but couldn't sleep. I got epilepsy. I had dizzy spells and kept passing out. Multiple times a day I felt like I was going to pass out, I got splotches of  vision and couldn't drive at night anymore. These symptoms lasted for 4 months. In July of 2021, I was diagnosed with POTS and started treatment with a clinic. I dropped out of college, (at the time I was a senior).  I can barely do any  exercise or handle anything stressful. I've improved a little but now take blood thinners, vitamin B shots, N-Acetyl-L-Cysteine supplements and vagus nerve vitamins.
LAB_DATA: My doctor ordered a tilt test and lots of specialty blood tests, eye tests, and an mri to confirm the POTS diagnosis.

Inability to close right eye fully. Sensation of numbness/tingling throughout right side of face, constant twitching under right eye, weakness with attempts at smiling  (right side of face). I had mild facial asymmetry growing up, but after the Covid vaccine, it has gotten so severe and limiting, at times I don?t want to be around people. It?s embarrassing. My eye is always dry, I have to try to force it to close more to make it look closer to how my left eye looks, and then all my right side facial muscles start twitching so much more because they are so weak. It?s awful and it seems to be getting continually worse as time goes on. It?s frustrating to have the CDC report it?s likely not a cause of Bell?s palsy to facial weakness, when I have had a stable course of only mild symptoms throughout my life for 31 years, and then immediately after receiving the vaccine, they got significantly (quality for life altering) worse. There is not just a correlation, there IS causation. Please feel free to contact me regarding more information. I want my case to be documented accurately.

Patient was given 2 cups of warm water and 2 glucose tablets because patient did not eat breakfast or lunch prior to the vaccination. Crushed ammonia capsules were also provided to the patients to smell and CPR was not needed. After 15 minutes of treatment, patients pulse and blood pressure normalized and he was observed in the pharmacy for another 20 minutes before he said he was fine and went home.

Patient notified recovery RN and nurse manager that she was feeling lightheaded and needed some water. Patient then started to feel anxious with increased respirations, nausea, and vomiting. BP was difficult to obtain. HR was at 60 BPM. 911 was called and paramedics arrived to assess patient. Patient felt better after vomiting and when the paramedics arrived. After paramedics assessed the patient, she declined further medical treatment and patient left clinic.
Bell's palsy.

I received a vaccination as it was the soonest available. 12-13 hours after the booster, I awoke to fever, sweats and chills. It was more mild than my second dose of Pfizer but persisted longer. I awoke to a fever of 101.5 at 4 am, which is when I took Tylenol. For most of the day, I had a low-grade fever, sweating and general fatigue. I took the day off. I felt generally weak/tired. I slept most of the morning and afternoon. Around 6 pm, I felt back to normal but still a bit weak.

Approximately one week post vaccination I began to feel a dull pain behind both eyes but primarily behind my left eye. This pain very slowly increased over the course of a week and one week in to symptoms I began feeling a sharp pain with eye movement. This lead  me to see my ophthalmologist (now three weeks after vaccine) After normal visual acuity and ocular pressure tests, and also noting my sensitivity to lights, he said I either had uveitis or scleritis and knowing that my symptoms had not improved with regular NSAIDS he prescribed oral prednisone. I saw him again one week later (4 weeks post vaccine) and my symptoms had not notably improved and the pain was even waking me from sleep. With an ultrasound imaging machine he documented fluid/inflammation in my posterior sclera bilaterally and prescribed continued prednisone. Over the next week pain on movement resolved but there is still severe pain behind my eyes and I still have intense light sensitivity. I am awaiting my next follow up (five weeks post vaccine).
OTHER_MEDS: Lithium, venlafaxine, vyvanse, levothyroxine, l-methyl folate, metformin, azelastine, melatonin, multi vitamin, iron, vitamin D, omeprazole, dulera
HISTORY: Asthma, poly cystic ovarian syndrome, bipolar disorder

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I looked at the clinic list in the morning. This patient`s DOB is and i miscalculated and thought that he had just turned 16. Patient came in at 5:40pm for his booster and the mother said he was here for his booster. I verified that it was at least 6 months from his 2nd dose, and since the kid was tall and 132 lbs... It never triggered in my mind to double check his age again. I noticed the error around 7:30pm when we finished batching. I called the doctor`s office and notified the nurse right away. The nurse took down the info and said that she will double check with the doctor and notify him as well. I then called and spoke to the patient`s parents and notified them also of the error. The parents were already aware as the nurse had called them already. I told them that it`s the same vaccine and dose as the first 2 shots and that most likely there shouldn`t be any issue. I told them that it`s an issue only because the has set the booster age from 16 and up. The parents said they scheduled the appt online and the system never blocked them from scheduling. They were concerned something might happen to their son. I told them to monitor should something happen and also to keep us updated on how he is doing.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt received pediatric pfizer vaccine at 5:25pm and immediately complained that her head hurt.  Her body went limp within seconds and a member of management was immediately called.  Patient was placed on the ground sitting up next to the immunization booth.  Her strength came back within minutes.  Mom moved patient to the immunization waiting chair and she complained that her vision was blurry and that she felt nauseous.  We got her water and the nausea and blurry vision went away.  Her O2 sat was 100% and pulse rate was 60 at 5:31pm with blood pressure of 90/38mmHG at 5:32pm.  Pharmacist continue to check on patient every 5 minutes for at least 45 minutes and patient's doing  good.
